# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-archipelago
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Angoon, a traditional Tlingit community home to 572 people, is the only settlement on the island, although an unpopulated section of the city of Juneau comprises 264.68 km2 (102.19 sq mi) (6.2 percent) of the island's land area near its northern end.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The island's total population at the 2000 census was 650.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The national monument is sacred to the Angoon Community Association, a Tlingit tribe, who live in Angoon on the western coast of the island.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The Tlingits fought to make protection for the island a part of ANILCA legislation, and continue to engage in stewardship of the island's natural resources.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Many of Angoon's residents make daily subsistence use of the national monument.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The Tlingit language name for the island is **Xootsnoowú**, which is commonly interpreted as "Fortress of the Bear(s)", and gives its name to hooch.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The island was named by British naval officer George Vancouver in honor of his Royal Navy employers, the Admiralty.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Joseph Whidbey, master of the *Discovery* during Vancouver's 1791–95 expedition, explored it in July–August 1794, in the process circumnavigating it.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The Admiralty Island National Monument was created December 1, 1978, by President Jimmy Carter.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] In the Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act Congress designated all but 18,351 acres (74.26 km2) (74 km2) of the monument as the Kootznoowoo Wilderness, ensuring that the vast bulk of this monument is permanently protected from development.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The monument is administered by the U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] In 1986 it was named a biosphere reserve along with Glacier Bay National Park under the Man and the Biosphere Programme.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Western hemlock, Sitka spruce and western redcedar dominate the prolific rainforest vegetation; wildlife in abundance includes brown bear, bald eagles, many species of salmon, whales, and deer.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Admiralty Island is home to the highest density of brown bears in North America.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] An estimated 1,600 brown bears inhabit the island, outnumbering Admiralty's human residents nearly three to one.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] It has more brown bears than the entire lower 48 states, and one of the highest densities of bald eagles in the world.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Murder Cove is located at the southernmost portion of the island and was home to the Tyee Company whaling station.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The Greens Creek mine is an underground silver, gold, zinc and lead mine located on the northwest end of the island, within the national monument.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Admiralty Island offers opportunities for outdoor recreation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The 32-mile Cross Admiralty Canoe Route is a popular destination for backcountry canoeing and kayaking, traversing the breadth of the island through a series of lakes, streams and trail portages, with several cabins and shelters along the way.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] While the modern route was laid out and constructed by the Civilian Conservation Corps in the 1930s, it follows traces long used by the island's native inhabitants for hunting, fishing and trading.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The Pack Creek Brown Bear Viewing Area offers visitors the opportunity to observe brown bears in their natural habitat as they fish for salmon and interact with one another during the summer months.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Permits are required for all visitors to Pack Creek; they can be obtained through the Forest Service.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] Over recent decades, various fishing and outdoor recreation lodges have opened up on the island with most of these lodges operating in the Tlingit town of Angoon.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] There’s also one lodge on a small, privately held plot of land within the national monument.
[src:alexander-archipelago/admiralty-island] The Point Retreat Light is located on the northern tip of Admiralty and was an important aid-to-navigation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is the largest U.S. state by area—comprising more total area than the next three largest states of Texas, California, and Montana combined—and is the world's largest semi-exclave and seventh-largest subnational division.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] With a population of 740,133 in 2024, it is the third-least populous and most sparsely populated state in the U.S., but the most populous territory in North America located mostly north of the 60th parallel, with more than quadruple the combined populations of Northern Canada and Greenland.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska contains the four largest cities in the United States by area, including the state capital, Juneau.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, and approximately half the state's residents live within its metropolitan area.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Indigenous people have lived in Alaska for thousands of years, and it is widely believed that the region served as the entry point for the initial settlement of the Americas by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Russian Empire was the first to actively colonize the area beginning in the 18th century, eventually establishing Russian America, which spanned most of the current state and promoted and maintained a native Alaskan Creole population.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The expense and logistical difficulty of maintaining this distant possession prompted its sale to the U.S. in 1867 for US$7.2 million, equivalent to $166 million in 2025.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The area went through several administrative changes before becoming organized as a territory on May 11, 1912.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It was admitted as the 49th state of the U.S. on January 3, 1959.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] An abundance of natural resources—including commercial fishing and the extraction of natural gas and oil—has enabled Alaska to have one of the highest per capita incomes in the United States, despite having one of the smallest economies.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Armed Forces bases and tourism also contribute to the economy; more than half of Alaska is federally owned, containing national forests, national parks, and wildlife refuges.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It is among the most irreligious states and one of the first to legalize recreational marijuana.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska has the highest proportion of Native Americans of any U.S. state, at 22 percent.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The name *Alaska* (Russian: Аля́ска, romanized: *Aljáska*) was introduced during the Russian colonial period when it was used to refer to the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It was derived from an Aleut-language idiom, *alaxsxaq*, meaning 'the mainland' or, more literally, 'the object towards which the action of the sea is directed'.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Numerous Indigenous peoples occupied Alaska for thousands of years before the arrival of European peoples to the area.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Linguistic and DNA studies done here have provided evidence for the settlement of North America by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] At the Upward Sun River site in the Tanana Valley in Alaska, remains of a six-week-old infant were found.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The baby's DNA showed that she belonged to a population that was genetically separate from other Native groups present elsewhere in the New World at the end of the Pleistocene.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Ben Potter, the University of Alaska Fairbanks archaeologist who unearthed the remains at the Upward Sun River site in 2013, named this new group Ancient Beringian.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Tlingit people developed a society with a matrilineal kinship system of property inheritance and descent in what is present Southeast Alaska, along with parts of British Columbia and the Yukon.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Also in the Southeast were the Haida, now well known for their unique arts.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Tsimshian people came to Alaska from British Columbia in 1887, when President Grover Cleveland, and later the U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Congress, granted them permission to settle on Annette Island and found the town of Metlakatla, Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] All three of these peoples, as well as other Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast, experienced smallpox outbreaks from the late 18th through the mid-19th century, with the most devastating epidemics occurring in the 1830s and 1860s, resulting in high fatalities and social disruption.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Some researchers believe the first Russian settlement in Alaska was established in the 17th century.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] According to this hypothesis, in 1648 several koches of Semyon Dezhnyov's expedition came ashore in Alaska by storm and founded this settlement.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] This hypothesis is based on the testimony of Chukchi geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who had visited Alaska in 1764–1765 and who had reported on a village on the Kheuveren River, populated by "bearded men" who "pray to the icons".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Some modern researchers associate the Kheuveren with the Koyuk River.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The first European vessel to reach Alaska is generally held to be the *St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Gabriel* under the authority of the surveyor M.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Fyodorov on August 21, 1732, during an expedition of Siberian Cossack A.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Shestakov and Russian explorer Dmitry Pavlutsky (1729–1735).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Another European contact with Alaska occurred in 1741, when Vitus Bering led an expedition for the Russian Navy aboard the *St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] After his crew returned to Russia with sea otter pelts judged to be the finest fur in the world, small associations of fur traders began to sail from the shores of Siberia toward the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The first permanent European settlement was founded in 1784.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] From 1774 to 1800, Spain sent several expeditions to Alaska to assert its claim over the Pacific Northwest, which it considered part of New Spain, administered from Mexico City, Mexico.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 1789, a Spanish settlement and fort were built in Nootka Sound.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] These expeditions gave names to places such as Valdez, Bucareli Sound, and Cordova.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Later, the Russian-American Company carried out an expanded colonization program during the early-to-mid-19th century.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Sitka, renamed New Archangel from 1804 to 1867, on Baranof Island in the Alexander Archipelago in what is now Southeast Alaska, became the capital of Russian America.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It remained the capital after the colony was transferred to the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Russians never fully colonized Alaska, and the colony was never very profitable.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Evidence of Russian settlement in names and churches survives throughout southeastern Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Seward, the United States Secretary of State under President Andrew Johnson, negotiated the Alaska Purchase, referred to pejoratively as Seward's Folly, with the Russians for $7.2 million.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Russian emperor Alexander II also planned the sale.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The purchase was made on March 30, 1867.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Six months later the commissioners arrived in Sitka and the formal transfer was arranged.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The flag-raising took place at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In the ceremony, 250 uniformed U.S. soldiers marched to the governor's house at "Castle Hill", where the Russian troops lowered the Russian flag and the U.S. flag was raised.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] This event is celebrated as Alaska Day, a legal holiday on October 18.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska was loosely governed by the military initially and was administered as a district starting in 1884, with a governor appointed by the United States president.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] A federal district court was headquartered in Sitka.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] For most of Alaska's first decade under the United States flag, Sitka was the only community inhabited by American settlers.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] They organized "a provisional city government", which was Alaska's first municipal government, but not in a legal sense.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Legislation allowing Alaskan communities to legally incorporate as cities arrived in 1900, and home rule for cities was extremely limited or unavailable until statehood took effect in 1959.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Starting in the 1890s and stretching in some places to the early 1910s, gold rushes in Alaska and the nearby Yukon Territory brought thousands of miners and settlers to Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 1912, Alaska was incorporated as an organized territory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska's capital, which had been in Sitka until 1906, was moved north to Juneau.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Construction of the Alaska Governor's Mansion began that same year.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] European immigrants from Norway and Sweden also settled in southeast Alaska, where they entered the fishing and logging industries.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] During World War II, the Aleutian Islands Campaign focused on Attu, Agattu and Kiska, all of which were occupied by the Empire of Japan.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] During the Japanese occupation, an American civilian and two United States Navy personnel were killed at Attu and Kiska respectively, and almost 50 Aleut civilians and eight sailors were interned in Japan.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] About half of the Aleuts died during the period of internment.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Unalaska/Dutch Harbor and Adak became significant bases for the United States Army, United States Army Air Forces and United States Navy.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The United States Lend-Lease program involved flying American warplanes through Canada to Fairbanks and then Nome.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Soviet pilots took possession of these aircraft, ferrying them to fight the German invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The construction of military bases contributed to the population growth of some Alaskan cities.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Statehood for Alaska was an important cause of James Wickersham early in his tenure as a congressional delegate.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Decades later, the statehood movement gained its first real momentum following a territorial referendum in 1946.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Alaska Statehood Committee and Alaska's Constitutional Convention soon followed.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Statehood supporters also found themselves fighting major battles against political foes, mostly in the U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska was officially proclaimed a state on January 3, 1959.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] On March 27, 1964, the Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the resultant tsunamis and landslides.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It was the fourth-most-powerful earthquake in recorded history, with a moment magnitude of 9.2, more than a thousand times as powerful as the 1989 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The time of day (5:36 pm), time of year (spring) and location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Good Friday earthquake lasted 4 minutes and 38 seconds.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other human-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks, and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there; survivors out-ran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Ruth A.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that the rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Broadcast journalist, Genie Chance, assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction as well as financially supporting the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of massive oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard founded the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The 1968 discovery of oil at Prudhoe Bay and the 1977 completion of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System led to an oil boom.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Royalty revenues from oil have funded large state budgets from 1980 onward.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Oil production was not the only economic value of Alaska's land.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Alaska discovered tourism as an important source of revenue.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Tourism became popular after World War II when military personnel stationed in the region returned home praising its natural splendor.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Alcan Highway, built during the war, and the Alaska Marine Highway System, completed in 1963, made the state more accessible than before.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Tourism has become increasingly important in Alaska, and today more than 1.4 million people visit the state each year.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] With tourism more vital to the economy, environmentalism rose in importance.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Because of the Act, Alaska now contains two-thirds of all American national parklands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Today, more than half of Alaskan land is owned by the Federal Government.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 1989, the *Exxon Valdez* hit a reef in the Prince William Sound, spilling more than 11 million gallons (42 megalitres) of crude oil over 1,100 miles (1,800 km) of coastline.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Today, the battle between philosophies of development and conservation is seen in the contentious debate over oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge and the proposed Pebble Mine.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Located at the northwest corner of North America very near to Asia, Alaska is the northernmost and westernmost state in the United States, but also has the most easterly longitude in the United States because the Aleutian Islands extend into the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is the only non-contiguous U.S. state on continental North America; about 500 miles (800 km) of Canadian territory consisting of British Columbia (in Canada) separates Alaska from Washington.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It is technically part of the continental U.S., but is not usually included in the colloquial use of the term; Alaska is not part of the contiguous U.S., often called "the Lower 48".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The capital city, Juneau, is situated on the mainland of the North American continent but is not connected by road to the rest of the North American highway system.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The largest lake in Alaska is Lake Illiamna.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is bordered by Canada's Yukon and British Columbia to the east (making it the only state to border only a Canadian territory); the Gulf of Alaska and the Pacific Ocean to the south and southwest; the Bering Sea, Bering Strait, and Chukchi Sea to the west; and the Arctic Ocean to the north.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska's territorial waters touch Russia's territorial waters in the Bering Strait, as the Russian Big Diomede Island and Alaskan Little Diomede Island are only 3 miles (4.8 km) apart.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska has a longer coastline than all the other U.S. states combined.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] At 663,268 square miles (1,717,856 km2) in total area, Alaska is by far the largest state in the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is more than twice the size of the second-largest U.S. state (Texas), and it is larger than the next three largest states (Texas, California, and Montana) combined.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is the seventh largest subnational division in the world.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] If it was an independent nation, it would be the 18th largest country in the world; almost the same size as Iran.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] With its myriad islands, Alaska has nearly 34,000 miles (55,000 km) of tidal shoreline.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Aleutian Islands chain extends west from the southern tip of the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Many active volcanoes are found in the Aleutians and in coastal regions.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Unimak Island, for example, is home to Mount Shishaldin, which is an occasionally smoldering volcano that rises to 10,000 feet (3,000 m) above the North Pacific.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The chain of volcanoes extends to Mount Spurr, west of Anchorage on the mainland.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Geologists have identified Alaska as part of Wrangellia, a large region consisting of multiple states and Canadian provinces in the Pacific Northwest, which is actively undergoing continent building.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] One of the world's largest tides occurs in Turnagain Arm, just south of Anchorage, where tidal differences can be more than 35 feet (10.7 m).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska has more than 409,000 natural lakes at least one hectare or bigger.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Marshlands and wetland permafrost cover 188,320 square miles (487,700 km2) (mostly in northern, western and southwest flatlands).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Glacier ice covers about 28,957 square miles (75,000 km2) of Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Bering Glacier is the largest glacier in North America, covering 2,008 square miles (5,200 km2) alone.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The most populous region of Alaska contains Anchorage, the Matanuska-Susitna Valley and the Kenai Peninsula.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Rural, mostly unpopulated areas south of the Alaska Range and west of the Wrangell Mountains also fall within the definition of South Central, as do the Prince William Sound area and the communities of Cordova and Valdez.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Also referred to as the Panhandle or Inside Passage, this is the region of Alaska closest to the contiguous states.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] As such, this was where most of the initial non-indigenous settlement occurred in the years following the Alaska Purchase.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The region is dominated by the Alexander Archipelago as well as the Tongass National Forest, the largest national forest in the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It contains the state capital Juneau, the former capital Sitka, and Ketchikan, at one time Alaska's largest city.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Alaska Marine Highway provides a vital surface transportation link throughout the area and country, as only three communities (Haines, Hyder and Skagway) enjoy direct connections to the contiguous North American road system.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Interior is the largest region of Alaska; much of it is uninhabited wilderness.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Fairbanks is the only large city in the region.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Denali National Park and Preserve is located here.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Denali, federally designated as Mount McKinley, is the highest mountain in North America and is also located here.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The North Slope is mostly tundra peppered with small villages.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The area is known for its massive reserves of crude oil and contains both the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska and the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The city of Utqiaġvik, formerly known as Barrow, is the northernmost city in the United States and is located here.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Northwest Arctic area, anchored by Kotzebue and also containing the Kobuk River valley, is often considered part of this region.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The respective Inupiat of the North Slope and of the Northwest Arctic seldom consider themselves to be one people.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Southwest Alaska is a sparsely inhabited region stretching some 500 miles (800 km) inland from the Bering Sea.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Most of the population lives along the coast.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Kodiak Island is also located in the Southwest.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The massive Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta, one of the largest river deltas in the world, is here.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Portions of the Alaska Peninsula are considered part of the Southwest, with the Aleutian Islands often (but not always) being grouped in as well.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] While primarily part of Southwest Alaska when grouped economically, the Aleutian islands are sometimes recognized as an alternate group from the rest of the region due to the geographic separation from the continent.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] More than 300 small volcanic islands make up this chain, which stretches more than 1,200 miles (1,900 km) into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Some of these islands fall in the Eastern Hemisphere, but the International Date Line was drawn west of 180° to keep the whole state, and thus the entire North American continent, within the same legal day.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Two of the islands, Attu and Kiska, were occupied by Japanese forces during World War II.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] As of 2023 the United States Bureau of Land Management manages 290 million surface and subsurface acres as public lands, including a multitude of national forests, national parks, national wildlife refuges, and federal mineral estate land.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Of these, the Bureau of Land Management manages 87 million acres (35 million hectares), or 23.8% of the state.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is managed by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It is the world's largest wildlife refuge, comprising 16 million acres (6.5 million hectares).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Of the remaining land area, the state of Alaska owns 101 million acres (41 million hectares), its entitlement under the Alaska Statehood Act.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] A portion of that acreage is occasionally ceded to the organized boroughs presented above, under the statutory provisions pertaining to newly formed boroughs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Smaller portions are set aside for rural subdivisions and other homesteading-related opportunities.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] These are not very popular due to the often remote and roadless locations.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The University of Alaska, as a land grant university, also owns substantial acreage which it manages independently.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Another 44 million acres (18 million hectares) are owned by 12 regional, and scores of local, Native corporations created under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) of 1971.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Regional Native corporation Doyon, Limited often promotes itself as the largest private landowner in Alaska in advertisements and other communications.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Provisions of ANCSA allowing the corporations' land holdings to be sold on the open market starting in 1991 were repealed before they could take effect.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Effectively, the corporations hold title (including subsurface title in many cases, a privilege denied to individual Alaskans) but cannot sell the land.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Individual Native allotments are sold on the open market.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Various private interests own the remaining land, totaling about one percent of the state.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is, by a large margin, the state with the smallest percentage of private land ownership when Native corporation holdings are excluded.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Alaska Heritage Resources Survey (AHRS) is a restricted inventory of all reported historic and prehistoric sites within the U.S. state of Alaska; it is maintained by the Office of History and Archaeology.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The survey's inventory of cultural resources includes objects, structures, buildings, sites, districts, and travel ways, with a general provision that they are more than fifty years old.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] As of 31 January 2012, more than 35,000 sites have been reported.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Unlike most of U.S. states, Alaska is not divided into counties.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Similarly to Louisiana's parishes, it is divided into *boroughs*.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Delegates to the Alaska Constitutional Convention wanted to avoid the pitfalls of the traditional county system and adopted their own unique model.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Many of the more densely populated parts of the state are part of Alaska's 16 boroughs, which function somewhat similarly to counties in other states.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Unlike county-equivalents in the other states, the boroughs do not cover the state's entire land area.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The area not part of any borough is referred to as the Unorganized Borough.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Unorganized Borough has no government of its own, but the U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Census Bureau in cooperation with the state divided the Unorganized Borough into 11 census areas solely for the purposes of statistical analysis and presentation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] A *recording district* is a mechanism for management of the public record in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The state is divided into 34 recording districts which are centrally administered under a state recorder.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] All recording districts use the same acceptance criteria, fee schedule, etc., for accepting documents into the public record.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Whereas many U.S. states use a three-tiered system of decentralization—state/county/township—most of Alaska uses two tiers—state/borough.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Owing to the low population density, most of the land is located in the Unorganized Borough.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] As the name implies, it has no intermediate borough government but is administered directly by the state government.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2000, 57.71% of Alaska's area has this status, with 13.05% of the population.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 1975, Anchorage merged the city government with the Greater Anchorage Area Borough to form the Municipality of Anchorage, containing the city proper and the communities of Eagle River, Chugiak, Peters Creek, Girdwood, Bird, and Indian.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Fairbanks has a separate borough (the Fairbanks North Star Borough) and municipality (the City of Fairbanks).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, home to 291,247 people in 2020.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The richest location in Alaska by per capita income is Denali ($42,245).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Yakutat, Sitka, Juneau, and Anchorage are the four largest cities in the U.S. by area.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In the 2020 United States census, Alaska has 355 incorporated cities and census-designated places (CDPs).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The tally of cities includes four unified municipalities, essentially the equivalent of a consolidated city–county.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The majority of these communities are located in the rural expanse of Alaska known as "The Bush" and are unconnected to that contiguous North American road network.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The table at the bottom of this section lists the 100 largest cities and census-designated places in Alaska, in population order.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Of Alaska's 2020 U.S. census population figure of 733,391, 16,655 people, or 2.27% of the population, did not live in an incorporated city or census-designated place.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Approximately three-quarters of that figure were people who live in urban and suburban neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city limits of Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer and Wasilla.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] CDPs have not been established for these areas by the United States Census Bureau.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Seven CDPs were established for the Ketchikan-area neighborhoods in the 1980 census (Clover Pass, Herring Cove, Ketchikan East, Mountain Point, Alaska Route 7, Pennock Island and Saxman East), but have not been used since.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The remaining population was scattered throughout Alaska, both within organized boroughs and in the Unorganized Borough, in largely remote areas.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is the coldest state in the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The climate in the south and southeastern Alaska is a mid-latitude oceanic climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfb*), and a subarctic oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfc*) in the northern parts, with cool summers and relatively mild winters.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] On an annual basis, the southeast is both the wettest and warmest part of Alaska with milder temperatures in the winter and high precipitation throughout the year.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Juneau averages over 50 in (130 cm) of precipitation a year, and Ketchikan averages over 150 in (380 cm).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] This is also the only region in Alaska in which the average daytime high temperature is above freezing during the winter months.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The climate of Anchorage and south central Alaska is mild by Alaskan standards due to the region's proximity to the seacoast.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] While the area gets less rain than southeast Alaska, it gets more snow, and days tend to be clearer.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] On average, Anchorage receives 16 in (41 cm) of precipitation a year, with around 75 in (190 cm) of snow, although there are areas in the south central which receive far more snow.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic climate (Köppen: *Dfc*) due to its brief, cool summers.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The climate of western Alaska is determined in large part by the Bering Sea and the Gulf of Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic oceanic climate in the southwest and a continental subarctic climate farther north.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The temperature is somewhat moderate considering how far north the area is.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] This region has a tremendous amount of variety in precipitation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] An area stretching from the northern side of the Seward Peninsula to the Kobuk River valley (i.e., the region around Kotzebue Sound) is technically a desert, with portions receiving less than 10 in (25 cm) of precipitation annually.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] On the other extreme, some locations between Dillingham and Bethel average around 100 in (250 cm) of precipitation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The climate of the interior of Alaska is subarctic and is a classic example of a continental subarctic climate, except in a few valleys where the climate approaches humid continental (Köppen: *Dfb*).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Some of the highest and lowest temperatures in Alaska occur around the area near Fairbanks.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Summers are warm, albeit generally short, and may have temperatures reaching into the 90s °F (the low-to-mid 30s °C).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In the long and very cold winters, the temperature can fall below −60 °F (−51 °C).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Precipitation is sparse in the Interior, often less than 10 in (25 cm) a year, but what precipitation falls in the winter tends to stay the entire winter.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The highest and lowest recorded temperatures in Alaska are both in the Interior.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The highest is 100 °F (38 °C) in Fort Yukon, which is just 8 mi or 13 km inside the arctic circle, on June 27, 1915, making Alaska tied with Hawaii as the state with the lowest high temperature in the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The lowest official Alaska temperature is −80 °F (−62 °C) in Prospect Creek on January 23, 1971, one degree above the lowest temperature recorded in continental North America (in Snag, Yukon, Canada).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The climate in the extreme north of Alaska, north of the Brooks Range, is Arctic (Köppen: *ET*) with long, very cold winters and short, cool summers.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Even in July, the average low temperature in Utqiaġvik is 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Precipitation is light in this part of Alaska, with many places averaging less than 10 in (25 cm) per year, mostly as snow which stays on the ground almost the entire year.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The United States Census Bureau found in the 2020 United States census that the population of Alaska was 733,391 on April 1, 2020, a 3.3% increase since the 2010 United States census.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In the 2010 United States Census, Alaska had a population of 710,231, an increase of 13.3%, up from 626,932 at the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2020, Alaska ranked as the 48th largest state by population, ahead of only Vermont and Wyoming.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is the least densely populated state, and one of the most sparsely populated areas in the world, at 1.2 inhabitants per square mile (0.46/km2).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The next state, Wyoming, has 5.8 inhabitants per square mile (2.2/km2).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is by far the largest U.S. state by area, and the tenth wealthiest, per capita income.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] As of 2018 due to its population size, it is one of 14 U.S. states that still have only one telephone area code.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,320 homeless people in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The 2019 American Community Survey estimated 60.2% of the population was white, 3.7% black or African American, 15.6% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 1.4% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 7.5% two or more races, and 7.3% Hispanic or Latin American.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] At the survey estimates, 7.8% of the total population was foreign-born from 2015 to 2019.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2015, 61.3% were white, 3.4% black or African American, 13.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.2% Asian, 0.9% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 0.3% some other race, and 7.7% multiracial.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Hispanics and Latin Americans were 7% of the state population in 2015.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] From 2015 to 2019, the largest Hispanic and Latin American groups were Mexican Americans, Puerto Ricans, and Cuban Americans.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The largest Asian groups living in the state were Filipinos, Korean Americans, and Japanese and Chinese Americans.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaska was 64.1% white, 14.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 5.4% Asian, 3.3% black or African American, 1.0% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 1.6% from some other race, and 7.3% from two or more races in 2010.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Hispanics or Latin Americans made up 5.5% of the population in 2010.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] As of 2011, 50.7% of Alaska's population younger than one year of age belonged to minority groups (i.e., did not have two parents of white ancestry).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 1960, the United States Census Bureau reported Alaska's population as 77.2% white, 3% black, and 18.8% American Indian and Alaska Native.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2018, the top countries of origin for Alaska's immigrants were the Philippines, Mexico, Canada, Thailand and South Korea.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In the 2011 American Community Survey, 83.4% of people over the age of five spoke only English at home.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] About 3.5% spoke Spanish at home, 2.2% spoke another Indo-European language, about 4.3% spoke an Asian language (including Tagalog), and about 5.3% spoke other languages at home.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey determined 83.7% spoke only English, and 16.3% spoke another language other than English.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The most spoken European language after English was Spanish, spoken by approximately 4.0% of the state population.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Collectively, Asian and Pacific Islander languages were spoken by 5.6% of Alaskans.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Since 2010, 5.2% of Alaskans speak one of the state's 20 Indigenous languages, known locally as "Native languages".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska is also known for a distinctive dialect of Russian, named Alaskan Russian.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Alaska Native Language Center at the University of Alaska Fairbanks claims that at least twenty Alaska Native languages exist and there are also some languages with different dialects.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Most of Alaska's Native languages belong to either the Eskimo–Aleut or Na-Dene language families.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Some languages are thought to be isolates (e.g., Haida) or have not yet been classified (e.g., Tsimshianic).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2014, nearly all of Alaska's Native languages were classified as either threatened, shifting, moribund, nearly extinct, or dormant languages.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In October 2014, the governor of Alaska signed a bill declaring the state's 20 Indigenous languages to have official status.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] This bill gave them symbolic recognition as official languages, though they have not been adopted for official use within the government.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In May 2024, a bill replaced Tanana with Middle Tanana and Lower Tanana, added Cupʼig and Wetał.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Multiple surveys have ranked Alaska among the most irreligious states.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] ChangePoint in south Anchorage (left) and Anchorage Baptist Temple in east Anchorage are Alaska's largest churches in terms of attendance and membership.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2010, per the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), about 34% of Alaska residents were members of religious congregations.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Of the religious population, roughly 4% were Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, 0.2% Baháʼí, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2010, the largest religious denominations in Alaska were the Catholic Church with 50,866 adherents; non-denominational Evangelicals with 38,070 adherents; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 32,170 adherents; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 19,891 adherents.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska has been identified, along with Washington and Oregon in the Pacific Northwest, as being the least religious states in the United States, in terms of church membership.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Pew Research Center in 2014 determined 62% of the adult population practiced Christianity.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Of the Christian denominations, Catholicism was the largest Christian group.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] When Protestant denominations were combined, Protestantism was the largest Christian tradition, with Evangelicalism being the largest movement within the Protestant group.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The unaffiliated population made up the largest non-Christian religious affiliation at 37%.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Atheists made up 5% of the population and the largest non-Christian religion was Buddhism.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute (PRRI) determined 57% of adults were Christian.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] By 2022, Christianity increased to 77% of the population according to the PRRI.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Through the Association of Religion Data Archives in 2020, its Christian population was dominated by non/inter-denominational Protestantism as the single largest Christian cohort, with 73,930 adherents.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Roman Catholics were second with 40,280 members; throughout its Christian population, non-denominational Christians had an adherence rate of 100.81 per 1,000 residents, and Catholics 54.92 per 1,000 residents.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Per 2014's Pew study, religion was seen as very important to 41% of the population, although 29% considered it somewhat important.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2014, Pew determined roughly 55% believed in God with absolute certainty, and 24% believed fairly certainly.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Reflecting the separate 2020 ARDA study, the 2014 Pew study showed 30% attended religious services once a week, 34% once or twice a month, and 36% seldom/never.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 1795, the first Russian Orthodox Church was established in Kodiak.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Intermarriage with Alaska Natives helped the Russian immigrants integrate into society.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] As a result, an increasing number of Russian Orthodox churches gradually became established within Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaska also has the largest Quaker population (by percentage) of any state.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2009, there were 6,000 Jews in Alaska, for whom observance of halakha may pose special problems.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Alaskan Hindus often share venues and celebrations with members of other Asian religious communities, including Sikhs and Jains.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaskan Hindus established the Sri Ganesha Temple of Alaska, making it the first Hindu Temple in Alaska and the northernmost Hindu Temple in the world.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] There are an estimated 2,000–3,000 Hindus in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The vast majority of Hindus live in Anchorage or Fairbanks.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Estimates for the number of Muslims in Alaska range from 2,000 to 5,000.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] In 2020, ARDA estimated there were 400 Muslims in the state.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] The Islamic Community Center of Anchorage began efforts in the late 1990s to construct a mosque in Anchorage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] They broke ground on a building in south Anchorage in 2010 and were nearing completion in late 2014.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] When completed, the mosque was the first in the state and one of the northernmost mosques in the world.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] There is also a Baháʼí center, and there were 690 adherents in 2020.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p01] Additionally, there were 469 adherents of Hinduism and Yoga altogether in 2020, and a small number of Buddhists were present.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In October 2022, Alaska had a total employment of 316,900.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The number of employer establishments was 21,077.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] As of August 2025, the unemployment rate was 4.7%.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The state's historically lowest unemployment rate was recorded in August 2022 at 3.8%, and its highest in May 2020 at 11.7%.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, Alaska's gross state product was $75.011 billion in 2025.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Its per capita personal income was $80,175 in 2025.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] According to a 2013 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Alaska had the fifth-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 6.75 percent.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The oil and gas industry dominates the Alaskan economy, with more than 80% of the state's revenues derived from petroleum extraction.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska's main export product, excluding oil and natural gas, is seafood, primarily salmon, cod, pollock and crab.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Agriculture represents a minuscule fraction of the Alaskan economy.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Agricultural production is primarily for consumption within the state and includes nursery stock, dairy products, vegetables, and livestock.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Manufacturing is limited, with most foodstuffs and general goods imported from elsewhere.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Employment is primarily in government and industries such as natural resource extraction, shipping, and transportation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Military bases are a significant component of the economy in Anchorage and the Fairbanks North Star and Kodiak Island boroughs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2025, 99.1% of Alaska businesses are small businesses and employ 54.2% of the state's workforce.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Federal subsidies are also an important part of the economy, allowing the state to keep taxes low.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Its industrial outputs are crude petroleum, natural gas, coal, gold, precious metals, zinc and other mining, seafood processing, timber and wood products.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] There is also a growing service and tourism sector.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Tourists have contributed to the economy by supporting local lodging.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska has vast energy resources, although its oil reserves have been largely depleted.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Major oil and gas reserves were found in the Alaska North Slope (ANS) and Cook Inlet basins, but according to the Energy Information Administration, by February 2014 Alaska had fallen to fourth place in the nation in crude oil production after Texas, North Dakota, and California.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope is still the second highest-yielding oil field in the United States, typically producing about 400,000 barrels per day (64,000 m3/d), although by early 2014 North Dakota's Bakken Formation was producing over 900,000 barrels per day (140,000 m3/d).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Trans-Alaska Pipeline can transport and pump up to 2.1 million barrels (330,000 m3) of crude oil per day, more than any other crude oil pipeline in the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Substantial coal deposits are found in Alaska's bituminous, sub-bituminous, and lignite coal basins.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The United States Geological Survey estimates that there are 85.4 trillion cubic feet (2,420 km3) of undiscovered, technically recoverable gas from natural gas hydrates on the Alaskan North Slope.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska also offers some of the highest hydroelectric power potential in the country from its numerous rivers.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Large swaths of the Alaskan coastline offer wind and geothermal energy potential as well.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska's economy depends heavily on increasingly expensive diesel fuel for heating, transportation, electric power and light.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Although wind and hydroelectric power are abundant and underdeveloped, proposals for statewide energy systems were judged uneconomical (at the time of the report, 2001) due to low (less than 50¢/gal) fuel prices, long distances and low population.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska Permanent Fund is a constitutionally authorized appropriation of oil revenues, established by voters in 1976 to manage a surplus in state petroleum revenues from oil, largely in anticipation of the then recently constructed Trans-Alaska Pipeline System.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The fund was originally proposed by Governor Keith Miller on the eve of the 1969 Prudhoe Bay lease sale, out of fear that the legislature would spend the entire proceeds of the sale (which amounted to $900 million) at once.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] It was later championed by Governor Jay Hammond and Kenai state representative Hugh Malone.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] It has served as an attractive political prospect ever since, diverting revenues which would normally be deposited into the general fund.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska Constitution was written so as to discourage dedicating state funds for a particular purpose.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund has become the rare exception to this, mostly due to the political climate of distrust existing during the time of its creation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] From its initial principal of $734,000, the fund has grown to $50 billion as a result of oil royalties and capital investment programs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Most if not all the principal is invested conservatively outside Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] This has led to frequent calls by Alaskan politicians for the Fund to make investments within Alaska, though such a stance has never gained momentum.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Every year, the state legislature takes out 8% from the earnings, puts 3% back into the principal for inflation proofing, and the remaining 5% is distributed to all qualifying Alaskans.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund is often considered to be one of the leading examples of a basic income policy in the world.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The cost of goods in Alaska has long been higher than in the contiguous 48 states.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Federal government employees, particularly United States Postal Service (USPS) workers and active-duty military members, receive a Cost of Living Allowance usually set at 25% of base pay because, while the cost of living has gone down, it is still one of the highest in the country.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Rural Alaska suffers from severely high prices for food and consumer goods compared to the rest of the country, due to the relatively limited transportation infrastructure.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Due to the northern climate and short growing season, relatively little farming occurs in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Most farms are in either the Matanuska Valley, about 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Anchorage, or on the Kenai Peninsula, about 60 miles (97 km) southwest of Anchorage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The short 100-day growing season limits the crops that can be grown, but the long sunny summer days make for productive growing seasons.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The primary crops are potatoes, carrots, lettuce, and cabbage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Tanana Valley is another notable agricultural locus, especially the Delta Junction area, about 100 miles (160 km) southeast of Fairbanks, with a sizable concentration of farms growing agronomic crops; these farms mostly lie north and east of Fort Greely.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] This area was largely set aside and developed under a state program spearheaded by Hammond during his second term as governor.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Delta-area crops consist predominantly of barley and hay.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] West of Fairbanks lies another concentration of small farms catering to restaurants, the hotel and tourist industry, and community-supported agriculture.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaskan agriculture has experienced a surge in growth of market gardeners, small farms and farmers' markets in recent years, with the highest percentage increase (46%) in the nation in growth in farmers' markets in 2011, compared to 17% nationwide.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The peony industry has also taken off, as the growing season allows farmers to harvest during a gap in supply elsewhere in the world, thereby filling a niche in the flower market.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska, with no counties, lacks county fairs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Instead, a small assortment of state and local fairs (with the Alaska State Fair in Palmer the largest), are held mostly in the late summer.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The fairs are mostly located in communities with historic or current agricultural activity, and feature local farmers exhibiting produce in addition to more high-profile commercial activities such as carnival rides, concerts and food.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] "Alaska Grown" is used as an agricultural slogan.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska has an abundance of seafood, with the primary fisheries in the Bering Sea and the North Pacific.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Seafood is one of the few food items that is often cheaper within the state than outside it.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Many Alaskans take advantage of salmon seasons to harvest portions of their household diet while fishing for subsistence, as well as sport.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] This includes fish taken by hook, net or wheel.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Hunting for subsistence, primarily caribou, moose, and Dall sheep is still common in the state, particularly in remote Bush communities.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] An example of a traditional native food is Akutaq, the Eskimo ice cream, which can consist of reindeer fat, seal oil, dried fish meat and local berries.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska's reindeer herding is concentrated on Seward Peninsula, where wild caribou can be prevented from mingling and migrating with the domesticated reindeer.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Most food in Alaska is transported into the state from "Outside" (the other 49 U.S. states), and shipping costs make food in the cities relatively expensive.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In rural areas, subsistence hunting and gathering is an essential activity because imported food is prohibitively expensive.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Although most small towns and villages in Alaska lie along the coastline, the cost of importing food to remote villages can be high because of the terrain and difficult road conditions, which change dramatically due to varying climate and precipitation changes.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Transport costs can reach 50¢ per pound ($1.10/kg) or higher in some remote areas during times of inclement weather or rough terrain conditions, if these locations can be reached at all.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The cost of delivering a gallon (3.8 L) of milk is about $3.50 in many villages where per capita income can be $20,000 or less.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Fuel cost per gallon is routinely twenty to thirty cents higher than the contiguous United States average, with only Hawaii having higher prices.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Some of Alaska's popular annual events are the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race from Anchorage to Nome, World Ice Art Championships in Fairbanks, the Blueberry Festival and Alaska Hummingbird Festival in Ketchikan, the Sitka Whale Fest, and the Stikine River Garnet Fest in Wrangell.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Stikine River attracts the largest springtime concentration of American bald eagles in the world.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Heritage Center celebrates the rich heritage of Alaska's 11 cultural groups.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Their purpose is to encourage cross-cultural exchanges among all people and enhance self-esteem among Native people.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Arts Foundation promotes and markets Native art from all regions and cultures in the State, using the internet.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Influences on music in Alaska include the traditional music of Alaska Natives as well as folk music brought by later immigrants from Russia and Europe.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Prominent musicians from Alaska include singer Jewel, traditional Aleut flautist Mary Youngblood, folk singer-songwriter Libby Roderick, Christian music singer-songwriter Lincoln Brewster, metal/post hardcore band 36 Crazyfists and the groups Pamyua and Portugal.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] There are many established music festivals in Alaska, including the Alaska Folk Festival, the Fairbanks Summer Arts Festival, the Anchorage Folk Festival, the Athabascan Old-Time Fiddling Festival, the Sitka Jazz Festival, the Sitka Summer Music Festival, and the Anchorage Chamber Music Festival.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The most prominent orchestra in Alaska is the Anchorage Symphony Orchestra, though the Fairbanks Symphony Orchestra and Juneau Symphony are also notable.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Anchorage Opera is currently the state's only professional opera company, though there are several volunteer and semi-professional organizations in the state as well.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The official state song of Alaska is "Alaska's Flag", which was adopted in 1955; it celebrates the flag of Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The 1983 Disney movie *Never Cry Wolf* was at least partially shot in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The 1991 film *White Fang*, based on Jack London's 1906 novel and starring Ethan Hawke, was filmed in and around Haines.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Steven Seagal's 1994 *On Deadly Ground*, starring Michael Caine, was filmed in part at the Worthington Glacier near Valdez.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Many reality television shows are filmed in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2011, the *Anchorage Daily News* found ten set in the state.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The following is a list of sporting venues, events, and teams based in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Troopers are Alaska's statewide police force.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] They have a long and storied history, but were not an official organization until 1941.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Before the force was officially organized, law enforcement in Alaska was handled by various federal agencies.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Larger towns usually have their own local police and some villages rely on "Public Safety Officers" who have police training but do not carry firearms.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In much of the state, the troopers serve as the only police force available.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In addition to enforcing traffic and criminal law, wildlife Troopers enforce hunting and fishing regulations.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Due to the varied terrain and wide scope of the Troopers' duties, they employ a wide variety of land, air, and water patrol vehicles.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Many rural communities in Alaska are considered "dry", having outlawed the importation of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Suicide rates for rural residents are higher than urban rates.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Domestic abuse and other violent crimes are at high levels in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] This is in part linked to alcohol abuse.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska has the highest rate of sexual assault in the nation, especially in rural areas.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The average age of sexually assaulted victims is 16 years old.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In four out of five cases, the suspects were relatives, friends, or acquaintances.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] As of 2022, CVS Health and Premera account for 47% and 46% of private health insurance, respectively.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Premera and Moda Health offer insurance on the federally-run Affordable Care Exchange.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Providence Alaska Medical Center in Anchorage is the largest hospital in the state as of 2021; Anchorage also hosts Alaska Regional Hospital and Alaska Native Medical Center.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska's other major cities such as Fairbanks and Juneau also have local hospitals.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In Southeast Alaska, Southeast Alaska Regional Health Consortium, runs healthcare facilities across 27 communities as of 2022, including hospitals in Sitka and Wrangell; although it originally served Native Americans only, it has expanded access and combined with other local facilities over time.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Education and Early Development administers many school districts in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In addition, the state operates a boarding school, Mt.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Edgecumbe High School in Sitka, and provides partial funding for other boarding schools, including Nenana Student Living Center in Nenana and The Galena Interior Learning Academy in Galena.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] There are more than a dozen colleges and universities in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Accredited universities in Alaska include the University of Alaska Anchorage, University of Alaska Fairbanks, University of Alaska Southeast, and Alaska Pacific University.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska is the only state that has no collegiate athletic programs that are members of NCAA Division I, although both Alaska-Fairbanks and Alaska-Anchorage maintain single sport membership in Division I for men's ice hockey.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development operates AVTEC, Alaska's Institute of Technology.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Campuses in Seward and Anchorage offer one-week to 11-month training programs in areas as diverse as Information Technology, Welding, Nursing, and Mechanics.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska has had a problem with a "brain drain".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Many of its young people, including most of the highest academic achievers, leave the state after high school graduation and do not return.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] As of 2013 Alaska did not have a law school or medical school.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The University of Alaska has attempted to combat this by offering partial four-year scholarships to the top 10% of Alaska high school graduates, via the Alaska Scholars Program.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Beginning in 1998, schools in rural Alaska must have at least ten students to retain funding from the state, and campuses not meeting the number close.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] This was due to the loss in oil revenues that previously propped up smaller rural schools.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2015, there was a proposal to raise that minimum to 25, but legislators in the state largely did not agree.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska has few road connections compared to the rest of the U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The state's road system, covering a relatively small area of the state, linking the central population centers and the Alaska Highway, the principal route out of the state through Canada.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The state capital, Juneau, is not accessible by road, with access only by ferry or flight; this has spurred debate over decades about moving the capital to a city on the road system, or building a road connection from Haines.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The western part of Alaska has no road system connecting the communities with the rest of Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Interstate Highways in Alaska consists of a total of 1,082 miles (1,741 km).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] These are mostly not built to Interstate Highway standards and their status as such is largely notional.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] A unique feature of the Alaska Highway system is the Anton Anderson Memorial Tunnel, an active Alaska Railroad tunnel that provides a paved roadway link with the isolated community of Whittier on Prince William Sound to the Seward Highway about 50 miles (80 km) southeast of Anchorage at Portage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] At 2.5 miles (4.0 km), the tunnel was the longest road tunnel in North America until 2007.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The tunnel is the longest combination road and rail tunnel in North America.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Southwest Alaska is largely coastal, sparsely populated, and unconnected to the road system.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Access to most communities in Southwest Alaska is primarily by air taxi, although larger towns like Kodiak, Bethel, King Salmon, Dillingham, and Dutch Harbor are accessible by scheduled air service.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Some coastal communities can be reached via the Alaska Marine Highway ferry.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Built around 1915, the Alaska Railroad (ARR) played a key role in the development of Alaska through the 20th century.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] It links shipping lanes on the North Pacific with Interior Alaska with tracks that run from Seward by way of South Central Alaska, passing through Anchorage, Eklutna, Wasilla, Talkeetna, Denali, and Fairbanks, with spurs to Whittier, Palmer and North Pole.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The cities, towns, villages, and region served by ARR tracks are known statewide as "The Railbelt".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In recent years, the ever-improving paved highway system began to eclipse the railroad's importance in Alaska's economy.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The railroad played a vital role in Alaska's development, moving freight into Alaska while transporting natural resources southward, such as coal from the Usibelli coal mine near Healy to Seward and gravel from the Matanuska Valley to Anchorage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] It is well known for its summertime tour passenger service.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska Railroad was one of the last railroads in North America to use cabooses in regular service and still uses them on some gravel trains.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] It continues to offer one of the last flag stop routes in the country.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] A stretch of about 60 miles (100 km) of track along an area north of Talkeetna remains inaccessible by road; the railroad provides the only transportation to rural homes and cabins in the area.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Until construction of the Parks Highway in the 1970s, the railroad provided the only land access to most of the region along its entire route.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In northern Southeast Alaska, the White Pass and Yukon Route also partly runs through the state from Skagway northwards into Canada (British Columbia and Yukon Territory), crossing the border at White Pass Summit.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] This line is now mainly used by tourists, often arriving by cruise liner at Skagway.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] It was featured in the 1983 BBC television series *Great Little Railways*.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] These two railroads are connected neither to each other nor any other railroad.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The nearest link to the North American railway network is the northwest terminus of the Canadian National Railway at Prince Rupert, British Columbia, several hundred miles to the southeast.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Congress authorized $6 million to study the feasibility of a rail link between Alaska, Canada, and the lower 48.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] As of 2021 the Alaska-Alberta Railway Development Corporation is in receivership.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Some private companies provides car float service between Whittier and Seattle.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Many cities, towns, and villages in Alaska don't have road or highway access.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The only modes of access involve travel by air, river, or the sea.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska's well-developed state-owned ferry system, known as the Alaska Marine Highway, serves the cities of southeast, the Gulf Coast and the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The ferries transport vehicles and passengers.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The system also operates a ferry service from Bellingham, Washington and Prince Rupert, British Columbia, in Canada through the Inside Passage to Skagway.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Inter-Island Ferry Authority also serves as an important marine link for many communities in the Prince of Wales Island region of Southeast and works in concert with the Alaska Marine Highway.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In recent years, cruise lines have created a summertime tourism market, mainly connecting the Pacific Northwest to Southeast Alaska and, to a lesser degree, towns along Alaska's gulf coast.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The population of Ketchikan for example fluctuates dramatically on many days—up to four large cruise ships can dock there at the same time.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Cities not served by road, sea, or river can be reached only by air, foot, dogsled, or snowmachine, accounting for Alaska's extremely well developed bush air services—an Alaskan novelty.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Anchorage, and to a lesser extent Fairbanks, is served by many major airlines.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Because of limited highway access, air travel remains the most efficient form of transportation in and out of the state.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Anchorage recently completed extensive remodeling and construction at Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport to help accommodate the upsurge in tourism.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2012–2013, Alaska received almost two million visitors.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Making regular flights to most villages and towns within the state commercially viable is difficult, so they are heavily subsidized by the federal government through the Essential Air Service program.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The bulk of remaining commercial flight offerings come from small regional commuter airlines such as Ravn Alaska, PenAir, and Frontier Flying Service.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The smallest towns and villages must rely on scheduled or chartered bush flying services using general aviation aircraft such as the Cessna Caravan, the most popular aircraft in use in the state.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Much of this service can be attributed to the Alaska bypass mail program which subsidizes bulk mail delivery to Alaskan rural communities.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The program requires 70% of that subsidy to go to carriers who offer passenger service to the communities.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Many communities have small air taxi services.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] These operations originated from the demand for customized transport to remote areas.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Perhaps the most quintessentially Alaskan plane is the bush seaplane.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The world's busiest seaplane base is Lake Hood, located next to Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport, where flights bound for remote villages without an airstrip carry passengers, cargo, and many items from stores and warehouse clubs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2006, Alaska had the highest number of pilots per capita of any U.S. state.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In Alaska there are 8,795 active pilot certificates as of 2020.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Another Alaskan transportation method is the dogsled.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In modern times, that is, any time after the mid- to late‑1920s, dog mushing is more of a sport than a true means of transportation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Races are held around the state, but the best known is the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, a 1,150-mile (1,850 km) trail from Anchorage to Nome, although the distance varies from year to year, the official distance is set at 1,049 miles or 1,688 km.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The race commemorates the famous 1925 serum run to Nome in which mushers and dogs like Togo and Balto took much-needed medicine to the diphtheria-stricken community of Nome when all other means of transportation had failed.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Mushers from all over the world come to Anchorage each March to compete for cash, prizes, and prestige.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The "Serum Run" is another sled dog race that more accurately follows the route of the famous 1925 relay, leaving from the community of Nenana, southwest of Fairbanks, to Nome.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In areas not served by road or rail, primary transportation in summer is by fourwheeler and in winter by snowmachine.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska's internet and other data transport systems are provided largely through the two major telecommunications companies: GCI and Alaska Communications.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] GCI owns and operates what it calls the Alaska United Fiber Optic system.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] As of late 2011, Alaska Communications had two fiber optic paths to the lower 48 and two more across Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In January 2011, it was reported that a $1 billion project to connect Asia and rural Alaska was being planned, aided in part by $350 million in stimulus from the federal government.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The state of Alaska employs approximately 16,000 people statewide.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Legislature consists of a 40-member House of Representatives and a 20-member Senate.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Senators serve four-year terms and House members two.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The governor of Alaska serves four-year terms.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The lieutenant governor runs separately from the governor in the primaries, but during the general election, the nominee for governor and nominee for lieutenant governor run together on the same ticket.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska's court system has four levels: the Alaska Supreme Court, the Alaska Court of Appeals, the Superior Court and the district courts.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The superior and district courts are trial courts.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Superior courts are courts of general jurisdiction, while district courts hear only certain types of cases, including misdemeanor criminal cases and civil cases valued up to $100,000.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court and the Court of Appeals are appellate courts.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Court of Appeals is required to hear appeals from certain lower-court decisions, including those regarding criminal prosecutions, juvenile delinquency, and habeas corpus.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court hears civil appeals and may in its discretion hear criminal appeals.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Although in its early years of statehood Alaska was a Democratic state, since the early 1970s it has been characterized as Republican-leaning.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Local political communities have often worked on issues related to land use development, fishing, tourism, and individual rights.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska Natives, while organized in and around their communities, have been active within the Native corporations.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] These have been given ownership over large tracts of land, which require stewardship.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska was formerly the only state in which possession of one ounce or less of marijuana in one's home was completely legal under state law, though the federal law remains in force.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The state has an independence movement favoring a vote on secession from the United States, with the Alaskan Independence Party.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Six Republicans and four Democrats have served as governor of Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Republican governor Wally Hickel was elected to the office for a second term in 1990 after leaving the Republican party and briefly joining the Alaskan Independence Party ticket just long enough to be reelected.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] He rejoined the Republican party in 1994.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska's voter initiative making marijuana legal took effect in February 2015, placing Alaska alongside Colorado and Washington, as well as Washington D.C., as the first three U.S. states where recreational marijuana is legal.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The law means people over 21 can consume small amounts of cannabis.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The first legal marijuana store opened in Valdez in October 2016.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] To finance state government operations, Alaska depends primarily on petroleum revenues and federal subsidies.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] This allows it to have the lowest individual tax burden in the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] It is one of five states with no sales tax, one of seven states with no individual income tax, and—along with New Hampshire—one of two that has neither.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Department of Revenue Tax Division reports regularly on the state's revenue sources.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The department issues an annual summary of its operations, including new state laws that directly affect the tax division.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2014, the Tax Foundation ranked Alaska as having the fourth most "business friendly" tax policy, behind only Wyoming, South Dakota, and Nevada.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] 89 municipalities collect a local sales tax, from 1.0 to 7.5%, typically 3–5%.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Other local taxes levied include raw fish taxes, hotel, motel, and bed-and-breakfast 'bed' taxes, severance taxes, liquor and tobacco taxes, gaming (pull tabs) taxes, tire taxes and fuel transfer taxes.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] A part of the revenue collected from certain state taxes and license fees, such as petroleum, aviation motor fuel, telephone cooperative, is shared with municipalities in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The fall in oil prices after the fracking boom in the early 2010s has decimated Alaska's state treasury, which has historically received about 85 percent of its revenue from taxes and fees imposed on oil and gas companies.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The state government has had to drastically reduce its budget, and has brought its budget shortfall from over $2 billion in 2016 to under $500 million by 2018.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2020, Alaska's state government budget was $4.8 billion, while projected government revenues were only $4.5 billion.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska regularly supports Republicans in presidential elections and has done so since statehood.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Republicans have won the state's electoral college votes in all but one election that it has participated in (1964).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] No state has voted for a Democratic presidential candidate fewer times.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska was carried by Democratic nominee Lyndon B.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Johnson during his landslide election in 1964, while the 1960 and 1968 elections were close.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Since 1972, Republicans have carried the state by large margins.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2008, Republican John McCain defeated Democrat Barack Obama in Alaska, 59.49% to 37.83%.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] McCain's running mate was Sarah Palin, the state's governor and the first Alaskan on a major party ticket.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Obama lost Alaska again in 2012, but he captured 40% of the state's vote in that election, making him the first Democrat to do so since 1968.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In 2020, Joe Biden received 42.77% of the vote for president, marking the high point for a Democratic presidential candidate since Johnson's 1964 victory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Alaska Bush, central Juneau, midtown and downtown Anchorage, and the areas surrounding the University of Alaska Fairbanks campus and Ester have been strongholds of the Democratic Party.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The Matanuska-Susitna Borough, the Kenai Peninsula, the majority of Fairbanks (including North Pole and the military base), and South Anchorage typically have the strongest Republican showing.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Alaska has a history of primary defeats for incumbent U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Senators, including Ernest Gruening, Mike Gravel, and Lisa Murkowski.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] However, Murkowski won re-election with a write-in campaign.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Despite this, Alaska has also seen long-serving members of Congress, such as Ted Stevens, who served as a U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Senator for 40 years, and Don Young, who held Alaska's sole U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] House seat for 49 years, from 1973 to 2022.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] In the 2020 election cycle, Alaskan voters approved Ballot Measure 2.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The measure passed by a margin of 1.1%, or about 4,000 votes.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The measure requires campaigns to disclose the original source and any intermediaries for campaign contributions over $2,000.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The measure also establishes non-partisan primaries, sometimes called jungle primaries, for statewide elections (like in Washington state and California) and ranked-choice voting, like in Maine.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] Measure 2 makes Alaska the third state with nonpartisan primaries for all statewide races, the second state with ranked choice voting, and the only state with both.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] The 2022 special election to fill Alaska's only U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] House seat, left vacant by the death of Don Young, was won by Mary Peltola.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] She became the first Democrat to win the House seat since 1972 and the first Alaskan Native elected to the United States Congress in history.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-p02] After winning a full term in the 2022 general election, Peltola lost reelection in 2024 to Republican Nick Begich III.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The **Alaska Purchase** was the purchase of Alaska from the Russian Empire by the United States for a sum of $7.2 million in 1867 (equivalent to $132 million in 2024).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] On May 15 of that year, the United States Senate ratified a bilateral treaty that had been signed on March 30, and American sovereignty became legally effective across the territory on October 18.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] During the first half of the 19th century, Russia had established a colonial presence in parts of North America, but few Russians ever settled in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Alexander II of Russia, having faced a catastrophic defeat in the Crimean War, began exploring the possibility of selling the state's Alaskan possessions, which, in any future war, would be difficult to defend from the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Seward, the U.S. secretary of state at the time, entered into negotiations with Russian diplomat Eduard de Stoeckl towards the United States' acquisition of Alaska after the American Civil War.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Seward and Steckel agreed to a treaty for the sale on March 30, 1867.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Reactions to the Alaska Purchase among Americans were mostly positive, as many believed that Alaska would serve as a base to expand American trade in Asia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Some opponents labeled the purchase as "**Seward's Folly**" or "**Seward's Icebox**" as they contended that the United States had acquired useless land.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Nearly all Russian settlers left Alaska in the aftermath of the purchase; Alaska would remain sparsely populated until the Klondike Gold Rush began in 1896.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Originally organized as the Department of Alaska, the area was renamed the District of Alaska in 1884 and the Territory of Alaska in 1912, ultimately becoming the modern-day state of Alaska in 1959.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Russian America was settled by *promyshlenniki*, merchants and fur trappers who expanded through Siberia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] They arrived in Alaska in 1732, and in 1799 the Russian-American Company (RAC) received a charter to hunt for fur.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] No colony was established, but the Russian Orthodox Church sent missionaries to the natives and built churches.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] About 700 Russians enforced sovereignty in a territory over twice as large as Texas.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] In 1821, Tsar Alexander I issued an edict declaring Russia's sovereignty over the North American Pacific coast north of the 51st parallel north.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The edict also forbade foreign ships to approach within 100 Italian miles (115 miles or 185 km) of the Russian claim.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] US secretary of state John Quincy Adams strongly protested the edict, which potentially threatened both the commerce and expansionary ambitions of the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Seeking favorable relations with the U.S., Alexander agreed to the Russo-American Treaty of 1824.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] In the treaty, Russia limited its claims to lands north of parallel 54°40′ north and also agreed to open Russian ports to U.S. ships.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] By the 1850s, a population of once 300,000 sea otters, who were skinned for their valuable fur, was almost extinct, and Russia needed money after being defeated by France and Britain in the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The California gold rush showed that if gold were discovered in Alaska, Americans and Canadians would overwhelm the Russian presence in what one scholar later described as "Siberia's Siberia".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] However, the principal reason for the sale was that the hard-to-defend colony would be easily conquered by British forces based in neighboring Canada in any future conflict, and Russia did not wish to see its archrival being next door just across the Bering Sea.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Therefore, Emperor Alexander II decided to sell the territory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The Russian government discussed the proposal in 1857 and 1858 and offered to sell the territory to the United States, hoping that its presence in the region would offset the plans of Britain.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] However, no deal was reached, as the risk of an American Civil War was a more pressing concern in Washington.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Grand Duke Konstantin, a younger brother of the Tsar, began to press for the handover of Russian America to the United States in 1857.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Konstantin's letter was shown to his brother, Tsar Alexander II, who wrote "this idea is worth considering" on the front page.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Supporters of Konstantin's proposal to immediately withdraw from North America included Admiral Yevfimy Putyatin and the Russian minister to the United States, Eduard de Stoeckl.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Gorchakov agreed with the necessity of abandoning Russian America but argued for a gradual process leading to its sale.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] He found a supporter in the naval minister and former chief manager of the Russian-American Company, Ferdinand von Wrangel.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Wrangel pressed for some proceeds to be invested in the economic development of Kamchatka and the Amur Basin.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The Emperor eventually sided with Gorchakov, deciding to postpone negotiations until the end of the RAC's patent, set to expire in 1861.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Over the winter of 1859–1860, Stoeckl held meetings with United States officials, though he had been instructed not to initiate discussions about the sale of the RAC assets.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Communicating primarily with Assistant Secretary of State John Appleton and California senator William M.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Gwin, Stoeckl reported the interest expressed by the Americans in acquiring Russian America.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] While President James Buchanan kept these hearings informal, preparations were made for further negotiations.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Stoeckl reported a conversation in which he asked "in passing" what price the U.S. government might pay for the Russian colony and Senator Gwin replied that they "might go as far as $5,000,000", a figure Gorchakov found far too low.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Stoeckl informed Appleton and Gwin of this, the latter saying that his Congressional colleagues in Oregon and California would support a larger figure.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Buchanan's increasingly unpopular presidency forced the matter to be shelved until a new presidential election.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] With the oncoming American Civil War, Stoeckl proposed a renewal of the RAC's charter.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Two of its ports were to be open to foreign traders and commercial agreements with Peru and Chile to be signed to give "a fresh jolt" to the company.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Russia continued to see an opportunity to weaken British power by causing British Columbia, including the Royal Navy base at Esquimalt, to be surrounded or annexed by American territory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Following the Union victory in the Civil War in 1865, the Tsar instructed Stoeckl to re-enter into negotiations with William H.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] President Andrew Johnson was busy with negotiations about Reconstruction, and Seward had alienated a number of Republicans, so both men believed that the purchase would help divert attention from domestic issues.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The negotiations concluded after an all-night session with the signing of the treaty at 04:00 on March 30, 1867.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The purchase price was set at $7.2 million (equivalent to $132 million in 2024), or about 2 cents per acre ($4.74/km2).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Much of the money Russia earned from the sale was reportedly paid to two Americans, Thomas and William Winans from Baltimore, Maryland, who were under contract with the Tsar to build and maintain Russia's railway system.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The Winans were seen as "the robber of the Russian Treasury", contract costs had ballooned exponentially.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The Winans received six and a half million rubles of the Alaskan sale proceeds.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The Russian name for the Alaska Peninsula was *Alyaska* ("Аляска") or *Alyeska*, from an Aleut word, *alashka* or *alaesksu*, meaning "great land" or "mainland".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The United States chose the name "Alaska" to refer to the area purchased from Russia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Seward told the nation that, according to Russian estimates, Alaska had about 60,000 inhabitants.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] This included about 10,500 who were under the direct government of the Russian fur company: about 8,000 indigenous people and 2,500 people of Russian or mixed Russian and indigenous descent (for example, having a Russian father and a native mother).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The remaining 50,000 or so were Inuit or Alaska Natives living outside of Russia's jurisdiction.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Seward also said that the Russians were settled at 23 trading posts, placed on accessible islands and at points along the coast.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] At smaller trading posts, typically only four or five Russians were stationed: their job was to collect furs from the natives for storage and then for shipment when the company's boats arrived to take the furs away.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] One was New Archangel (now named Sitka), established in 1804 to handle the valuable trade in the skins of sea otters; in 1867, it had 116 small log cabins and 968 residents.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Paul, in the Pribilof Islands, which had 100 homes and 283 residents, and was the center of the seal fur industry.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Seward and many other Americans expected that Asia would become an important market for U.S. products, and that Alaska would serve as a base for American trade with Asia and globally, and for the extension of American power into the Pacific.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Senator Charles Sumner, chair of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, sponsored the Senate bill authorizing the U.S. to approve the treaty to acquire the territory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] He not only agreed about the benefit to trade, but also said he expected the territory to be valuable on its own; having studied the records of explorers, he believed it contained valuable animals and forests.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] He compared the acquisition to contemporary European colonial acquisitions, such as the French conquest of Algeria.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The United States Senate approved the treaty by a vote of 37 to 2.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Many Americans believed in 1867 that the purchase process had been corrupt, but W.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Dall in 1872 wrote that "there can be no doubt that the feelings of a majority of the citizens of the United States are in favor of it." The notion that the purchase was unpopular among Americans is, a scholar wrote 120 years later, "one of the strongest historical myths in American history.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] It persists despite conclusive evidence to the contrary, and the efforts of the best historians to dispel it", likely in part because it fits American and Alaskan writers' view of the territory as distinct and filled with self-reliant pioneers.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] A majority of newspapers either supported the purchase or were neutral.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] A review of dozens of contemporary newspapers found general support for the purchase, especially in California; most of 48 major newspapers supported the purchase.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Public opinion was not universally positive; to some the purchase was known as "Seward's folly", "Walrussia", or "Seward's icebox".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Editorials contended that taxpayer money had been wasted on a "polar bear garden".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Forty-five percent of supportive newspapers cited the increased potential for annexing British Columbia in their support, and *The New York Times* stated that, consistent with Seward's reason, Alaska would increase American trade with East Asia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The principal urban newspaper that opposed the purchase was the *New York Tribune*, published by Seward opponent Horace Greeley.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The ongoing controversy over Reconstruction spread to other acts, including the Alaska purchase.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Some opposed the United States obtaining its first non-contiguous territory, seeing it as a colony; others saw no need to pay for land that they expected the country to obtain through manifest destiny.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The transfer ceremony took place in Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Russian and American soldiers paraded in front of the governor's house; the Russian flag was lowered and the American flag raised amid peals of artillery.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] A description of the events was published in Finland six years later.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] After the flag transition was completed, Captain of 2nd Rank Aleksei Alekseyevich Peshchurov said, "General Rousseau, by authority from His Majesty, the Emperor of Russia, I transfer to the United States the territory of Alaska." General Lovell Rousseau accepted the territory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] (Peshchurov had been sent to Sitka as commissioner of the Russian government in the transfer of Alaska.) A number of forts, blockhouses and timber buildings were handed over to the Americans.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The troops occupied the barracks; General Jefferson C.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Davis established his residence in the governor's house, and most of the Russian citizens went home, leaving a few traders and priests who chose to remain.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] After the transfer, a number of Russian citizens remained in Sitka, but nearly all of them very soon decided to return to Russia, which was still possible at the expense of the Russian-American Company.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Moreover, Ahllund's article is the only known description of the return voyage on the *Winged Arrow*, a ship that was specially purchased to transport the Russians back to their native country.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] "The over-crowded vessel, with crewmen who got roaring drunk at every port, must have made the voyage a memorable one." Ahllund mentions stops at the Sandwich (Hawaiian) Islands, Tahiti, Brazil, London, and finally Kronstadt, the port for St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Petersburg, where they arrived on August 28, 1869.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] American settlers who shared Sumner's belief in the riches of Alaska rushed to the territory but found that much capital was required to exploit its resources, many of which could also be found closer to markets in the contiguous United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Most soon left, and by 1873, Sitka's population had declined from about 2,500 to a few hundred.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The United States acquired an area over twice as large as Texas, but it was not until the great Klondike Gold Rush in 1896 that Alaska generally came to be seen as a valuable addition to U.S. territory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The seal fishery was one of the chief considerations that induced the United States to purchase Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] It provided considerable revenue by the lease of the privilege of taking seals, an amount that was eventually more than the price paid for Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] From 1870 to 1890, the seal fisheries yielded 100,000 skins a year.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The company to which the administration of the fisheries was entrusted by a lease from the US government paid a rental of $50,000 per annum and in addition thereto $2.62+1⁄2 per skin for the total number taken.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The skins were transported to London to be dressed and prepared for world markets.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The business grew so large that the earnings of English laborers after the acquisition of Alaska by the United States amounted by 1890 to $12,000,000.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] However, exclusive US control of this resource was eventually challenged, and the Bering Sea Controversy resulted when the United States seized over 150 sealing ships flying the British flag, based out of the coast of British Columbia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The conflict between the United States and Britain was resolved by an arbitration tribunal in 1893.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The waters of the Bering Sea were deemed to be international waters, contrary to the US contention that they were an internal sea.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The US was required to make a payment to Britain, and both nations were required to follow regulations developed to preserve the resource.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] The purchase of Alaska has been referenced as a "bargain basement deal" and as the principal positive accomplishment of the otherwise much-maligned presidency of Andrew Johnson.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Barker has argued that the US federal government has not earned a positive financial return on the purchase of Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] According to Barker, tax revenue and mineral and energy royalties to the federal government have been less than federal costs of governing Alaska plus interest on the borrowed funds used for the purchase.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Miller has taken the argument further by contending that US oil companies that developed Alaskan petroleum resources did not earn enough profits to compensate for the risks that they incurred.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alaska-purchase] Alaska Day is a holiday for all state workers.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] Little is known about Chirikov's early life other than that the Russian was born in 1703.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] There is a claim, which originated in 1941, that he was the son of one of Peter the Great's master carpenters.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] It is known that Chirikov began his service in the Russian Imperial Navy in 1716, and later in 1721 he graduated from the Naval Academy with the rank of Sub-lieutenant.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] In 1725–1730 and 1733–1743, he was Vitus Bering's deputy during the First and the Second Kamchatka expeditions, having been made a captain in 1733.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] In June 1741 Chirikov in the *St Paul* and Vitus Bering in the *St Peter*, who he was serving under, left Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky and headed east.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] Some time after 20 June they were separated by a storm and never saw each other again.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] On 15 July 1741 Chirikov saw land at Baker Island off Prince of Wales Island at the south end of the Alaska Panhandle.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] This was about 450 miles southeast of Bering's landfall near Mount St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] Elias at the north end of the panhandle.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] Unable to find a harbor he sailed north along Baranov Island past the later Russian base at Sitka.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] He sent out a longboat to find an anchorage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] When it did not return after a week he sent out his second longboat which also failed to return.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] Now without any small boats Chirikov had no way of searching for the two longboats or landing on the coast to explore or replenish his supply of fresh water.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] After waiting as long as possible, he abandoned the longboats to their fate and on 27 July sailed west.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] He sighted the Kenai Peninsula, Kodiak Island and Adak Island near the western end of the Aleutians.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] With water critically low he reached Petropavlovsk on 12 October 1741.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] In 1742, Chirikov was in charge of a search party for Bering's ship *St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] During this trip, he located Attu Island.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] Chirikov took part in creating the final map of the Russian discoveries in the Pacific Ocean (1746).
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] In 1746 was assigned the Director of Academy of the Naval Guard, St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] Chirikov's name is given to Capes of the Kyūshū Island, Attu Island, Anadyr Bay, Tauyskaya Bay, an underwater mountain in the Pacific Ocean, Chirikof Island and Cape Chirikof at the westernmost point of Baker Island.
[src:alexander-archipelago/aleksei-chirikov] Chirikov died on November 14, 1748, in Moscow due to scurvy.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The **Alexander Archipelago wolf** (***Canis lupus ligoni***), also known as the **Islands wolf**, is a subspecies of the gray wolf.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The coastal wolves of southeast Alaska inhabit the area that includes the Alexander Archipelago, its islands, and a narrow strip of rugged coastline that is biologically isolated from the rest of North America by the Coast Mountains.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The Tongass National Forest comprises about 80% of the region.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In 1993, a petition to list the Alexander Archipelago wolf as threatened under the U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Endangered Species Act was lodged with the U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The agency decided in 1997 that listing was not warranted at that time.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In the interim, a multiagency conservation assessment of the species was published.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In 2011, a second petition to list the species as either threatened or endangered was filed with the Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] It referenced scientific studies and other information that had arisen over the intervening 14 years.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In March 2014, in response to the petition, the agency made a positive initial finding that listing the species as threatened or endangered "may be warranted" and that it will prepare a formal status review.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] This wolf is recognized as a subspecies of *Canis lupus* in the taxonomic authority *Mammal Species of the World (2005)*.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Early taxonomists were able to determine that the Alexander Archipelago wolf was its own unique subspecies due to "common cranial characteristics".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Taxonomists have suggested more recently that the species may have originated from another subspecies known as *C. l. nubilus*.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Studies using mitochondrial DNA have indicated that the wolves of coastal southeast Alaska are genetically distinct from inland gray wolves, reflecting a pattern also observed in other taxa.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] These findings call into question the taxonomic classification of *C.l. nulibus* proposed by Nowak.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Another study found that the wolves of coastal British Columbia were genetically and ecologically distinct from the inland wolves, including other wolves from inland British Columbia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In 2016, two studies compared the DNA sequences of 42,000 single-nucleotide polymorphisms in North American gray wolves and found the coastal wolves to be genetically and phenotypically distinct from other wolves.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] They share the same habitat and prey species, and form one of the study's six identified ecotypes - a genetically and ecologically distinct population separated from other populations by their different types of habitat.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The local adaptation of a wolf ecotype most likely reflects the wolf's preference to remain in the type of habitat that it was born into.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Wolves that prey on fish and small deer in wet, coastal environments tend to be smaller than other wolves.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Typically smaller than the other North American subspecies of wolf, the Alexander Archipelago wolf averages between 30 and 50 lb (14 and 23 kg).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] They are about 3+1⁄2 ft (1.1 m) long and 2 ft (0.61 m) tall at the shoulder.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Their coat is generally a dark gray, with varying patterns of lighter shades.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Individuals from different islands in the archipelago have a propensity for different color phases, from pure black to combinations of black and white to a much brighter cinnamon color.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The primary prey of this species is the Sitka black-tailed deer, which comprises as much as 90% of an individual's diet.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The next-closest consumed species, less than 10%, is the North American beaver.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The average Alexander Archipelago wolf eats an estimated 26 deer per year.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] This habit of feeding almost entirely on a single species is peculiar to this wolf, and is not seen in other North American wolf species.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] This subspecies consumes large amounts of salmon in addition to deer, beaver, mountain goat, and small mammals.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Salmon make up about 10-25% of their diet.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Salmon are attributed with allowing the subspecies to have one of the higher pup survivorship rates (90%) of the species.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The range of *C. lupus ligoni* covers all of southeastern Alaska (the Alaskan panhandle) except the Admiralty, Baranof, and Chichagof Islands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] A population survey (from a mid-1990s radio-collar study) produced a region-wide estimate of 750 to 1,100 wolves, with the number of wolves in the autumn of 1994 (before trapping season) estimated to be 908.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] That study was conducted on Prince of Wales Island, with the region-wide estimate being based on an extrapolation on the varying habitat capability for prey.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The Prince of Wales population was estimated to be 300–350.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] From Environment New Jersey: "The Alexander Archipelago wolf is one of the world's rarest wolf subspecies, and the islands that make up the Tongass National Forest are its only home in the United States.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] During field work in the summer of 2010, the Alaska Department of Fish and Game (ADFG) determined that Prince of Wales Island's wolf population had declined sharply; the ADFG was unable to collect enough wolf scats to make a population estimate based on DNA.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Reportedly, "only a 'small fraction' of the expected number of scats" were found during this effort, in which a number of previously known denning sites were checked, and transects were checked over an extensive part of the island.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In a regulatory proposal, given at the Alaska Board of Game's November 2010 meeting to help protect the species, ADFG estimated the island's wolf population to be only 150, down by over 50% of the estimated 300–350 wolves from the 1990s radio-collar survey.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In southeastern Alaska, wolf pups are usually born during the final two weeks of April.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Dens are usually constructed 4–5 weeks prior to the birth.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The Alexander Archipelago wolf first arrived in Alaska sometime between 7,000 and 8,000 years ago, after the end of the Wisconsin glaciation period.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The species was likely following the migration of the Sitka deer as they traveled north because of geographical and climate change in the area.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The first observation of concern for the possible instability of the Alexander Archipelago wolf population was by a USDA Forest Service-sponsored interagency committee.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] This concern came about because of the extensive logging being conducted in the region's forest, under the Tongass Land Management Plan.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] A petition was presented to the United States Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) in December 1993 by the Biodiversity Legal Foundation and an independent biologist, requesting the Alexander Archipelago wolf to be listed as a threatened species under the Endangered Species Act.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] After the assessment was completed, more studies were undertaken to understand exactly how the Alexander Archipelago wolf fits into the food chain and what effect extensive logging would cause.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] After study that, between 1995 and 2045, the population of the Alexander Archipelago wolf was surmised to "decline as much as 25%", along with Sitka deer population declining by 28% within the same time.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In 1994, the FWS issued a memo stating, "not protecting the wolf would be the 'least controversial option'".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] This was in regards to the logging companies and lobbyists that opposed restrictions on logging in the area, which protecting the Alexander Archipelago wolf would create.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In 1997, the petition was denied due to the findings that wolves in southeast Alaska would not be in danger of extinction within the foreseeable future.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Jack Ward Thomas wrote in his book, *Jack Ward Thomas: the journals of a Forest Service chief*, about a meeting held in 1995 in regards to a consideration by the Forest Service to list the Alexander Archipelago wolf and the Queen Charlotte goshawk as threatened.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The meeting was between Thomas, Undersecretary James Lyons, Deputy Undersecretary Adela Backiel, and Alaska Regional Forester Phil Janik, all on behalf of the Forest Service, and Ted Stevens, Frank Murkowski, and Don Young.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The main argument was from Stevens, Murkowski, and Young, who believed that the Forest Service was trying to purposefully limit the lumber market in Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] They demanded that the two species not be listed or that negative legislation would follow, likely resulting in budget and personnel cuts for the Forest Service.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The Tongass Land Management Plan (forest plan) was revised in 1997 after immense pressure from environmental groups to list the Alexander Archipelago wolf as threatened.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The plan included a standard and guideline to sustain a habitat carrying capacity of least 18 Sitka deer per square mile to provide adequate prey and to limit the density of roads (i.e. miles of road per square mile).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The forest plan also established a system of habitat reserves.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] On the basis of the new plan, shortly afterward, FWS made a final determination that listing the wolf as threatened was unwarranted.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In 2011, a 103-page petition to list the Alexander Archipelago wolf as a threatened or endangered species under the Endangered Species Act was filed with the US Fish and Wildlife Service by the Center for Biological Diversity and Greenpeace on August 10, 2011.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The petition requested consideration for a separate listing of the Prince of Wales Island population because it is believed to be a distinct population segment, as well as a listing for the subspecies as a whole.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In March 2014 the agency published a finding in the Federal Register that listing the Alexander Archipelago wolf "may be warranted." The finding was positive on three of the five factors that the Endangered Species Act requires the agency to consider.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The agencies say several years may be needed to get funding to complete the review, but 3 days after the finding was published, the petitioners notified the agency they intend to sue to expedite the process.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The FWS would prefer to leave management of the wolf with the state, if the state will create a viable plan for wolf conservation; however, the service will list the species if it determines doing so is necessary to protect the species' existence.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The supervisor of the Tongass National Forest, Forrest Cole, said the Forest Service will cooperate with the FWS in evaluating the status of the species.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The Alaska Department of Fish and Game's Division of Wildlife Conservation does not believe the Alexander Archipelago wolf is at risk now or threatened with the risk of extinction in the foreseeable future.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] However, the division's primary researcher on the status of the species, Dr.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Greenpeace and the Cascadia Wildlands Project pointed out in 2008 that data the Forest Service was using were known to be prone to cause overestimation of the carrying capacity for deer, the wolves' primary prey.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Furthermore, the conversion factor, known as the "deer multiplier", used in the calculations was incorrectly applied, causing a 30% overestimation of carrying capacity and corresponding underestimation of impacts.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The two organizations determined, in total, the carrying capacity for the Sitka deer in places throughout the Tongass had been generally been overestimated by the Forest Service in its timber planning, by as much as 120% (varying geographically due to the faulty data).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In 2008, Greenpeace and the Cascadia Wildlands Project sued to stop the Forest Service from proceeding with four timber sales on the Tongass NF slated to extract around "30 million board-feet of Tongass timber", an amount close to the annual volume then being logged.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The sales are on Prince of Wales, Kupreanof, Mitkof, and Revillagigedo Islands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The suit challenged the agency's method of calculating the impact of logging on habitat carrying capacity for deer.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In a radio story, the plaintiff's spokesman explained that the data being used to represent habitat quality are actually uncorrelated to habitat quality, and that the deer multiplier mentioned above was misused according to the science under which it was derived.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The story points to the Forest Service's underestimation of impacts not only to wolves but to subsistence deer hunters.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In May 2010, US District Judge Ralph Beistline denied the plaintiff's motion for summary judgment, saying he "found no wrongdoing on the part of the Forest Service" and it was a "scientific disagreement".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The plaintiffs appealed the decision to the 9th US Circuit Court of Appeals (case 10-35567).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] A three-judge panel (Arthur Alarcón, Susan Graber, and Jay Bybee) heard oral arguments in the appeal on May 3, 2011 The panel ruled in favor of the plaintiffs on August 2, 2011, reversing in part, vacating in part and remanding the district court's decision.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] "We do not think that USFS has adequately explained its decision to approve the four logging projects in the Tongass. ...
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] USFS has failed to explain how it ended up with a table that identifies 100 deer per square mile as a maximum carrying capacity, but allows 130 deer per square mile as a potential carrying capacity.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] 'The agency is obligated to articulate a rational connection between the facts found and the choices made,' which the agency has not done here.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] "We have similar questions about USFS's use of VolStrata data, which identifies total timber volume and not forest structure, to approve the projects, where forest structure—and not total timber volume—is relevant to the habitability of a piece of land.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] USFS itself has recognized the limitations in the VolStrata data. ...
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Because we must remand to the agency to re-examine its Deer Model, we need not decide whether the use of the VolStrata data was arbitrary and capricious.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] He also said, "The purpose of the lawsuit is to make the Forest Service go back and do its analysis right on these timber sales.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] In January 2010, the Forest Service was sued over its 73 million-board-ft Logjam timber sale on Prince of Wales Island, by Tongass Conservation Society, Cascadia Wildlands, and Greenpeace.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] At issue is the impact of excessive road density on wolf mortality and further loss of habitat for the primary prey (deer), among other issues.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The plaintiff's motion for summary judgement was denied by the US District Court, Alaska, in September, and the case has been appealed to the 9th US Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The court scheduled oral arguments before Judges Betty Fletcher, Andrew Kleinfeld, and Consuelo Callahan for July 29, 2011, sitting in Anchorage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] The petition was filled by environmental groups concerned about wolves on Prince of Wales Island where they are subject to legal hunting and trapping.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago-wolf] Fish and Wildlife Service found in 2023 that it was not currently warranted.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The **Alexander Archipelago** (Russian: Архипелаг Александра) is a 300-mile-long (480 km) archipelago (group of islands) in North America lying off the southeastern coast of Alaska.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] It contains about 1,100 islands, the tops of submerged coastal mountains that rise steeply from the Pacific Ocean.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] Deep channels and fjords separate the islands and cut them off from the mainland.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The islands shelter the northern part of the Inside Passage as it winds its way among them.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The islands have steep, irregular coasts and dense evergreen and temperate rain forests; most are accessible only by boat or by airplane.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The vast majority of the islands are part of the Tongass National Forest.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] All the islands are rugged, densely forested, and have an abundance of wildlife.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The Tlingit and Kaigani Haida people are native to the area.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The Tsimshian people found on Annette Island are not originally from the area, having immigrated to the region from British Columbia in the late 19th century.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] Ketchikan on Revillagigedo Island and Sitka on Baranof Island are the largest towns on the islands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The most populous neighborhoods of the largest town in the region, Juneau, stand on the mainland, though portions of the city also lie on Douglas Island, which is a part of the archipelago.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] Tourism, fishing, and logging are the main industries of the islands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The first European to visit the archipelago was the Russian navigator Aleksei Chirikov in 1741, who sighted the coasts of Noyes and Baker Islands (both off the west coast of Prince of Wales Island), as well as Baranof, Chichagof, Kruzof, and Yakobi Islands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] In 1774, Juan José Pérez Hernández sighted the south coast of Dall Island, while Juan Francisco de la Bodega y Quadra entered Bucareli Bay off Prince of Wales Island the following year.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] In 1792, Jacinto Caamaño sighted Revillagigedo Island and the Gravina Islands, discovering Clarence Strait.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] George Vancouver and his men made an extensive survey of the archipelago in 1793 and 1794, circumnavigating both Revillagigedo and Admiralty Islands, charting the entirety of Kuiu Island, the east sides of Baranof and Chichagof Islands, and Etolin, Wrangell, Zarembo, Mitkof, and Kupreanof Islands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] Within a decade, the Russians had traversed Peril Strait separating Chichagof and Baranof Islands, and in the following decades found the straits and passages separating several of the other major islands.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] An 1844 Russian chart shows Kupreanof separated from Mitkof Island and Etolin, Wrangell, Woronkofski, and Zarembo Islands separated from each other.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The archipelago was a locus of the Maritime Fur Trade during the early 19th century.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] Control of the islands passed from Russia to the United States with the Alaska Purchase in 1867.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] According to Donald Orth's *Dictionary of Alaska Place Names* (p.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] 64), the Alexander Archipelago received its name from the U.S.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] The island chain is named for Tsar Alexander II of Russia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-archipelago] On an 1860 map of Russian America (Alaska), the island group is called the King George III Archipelago.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] However, many of these reforms were met with intense backlash and cut back or reversed entirely, and Alexander eventually shifted towards a considerably more conservative political stance following an assassination attempt against him in 1866.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The foreign policy of Alexander was relatively pacifist, especially in comparison to his father's, although he did continue the Russian Empire's expansionist campaigns into the Far East, the Caucasus, and Central Asia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] As a consequence of the Great Game and the Crimean War, Alexander was particularly opposed to and wary of the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He was also notably supportive of the United States; Alexander backed the Union during the American Civil War and even sent Russian warships to New York Harbor and San Francisco Bay to deter attacks by the Confederate Navy.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1867, he sold Alaska to the United States, owing partly to his concern that it would be nearly impossible to prevent the Russian Empire's North American colonies, which bordered British Columbia and the North-Western Territory, from falling into British hands in the event of another war.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Seeking peace and stability in the European continent, he moved away from bellicose France upon the fall of Napoleon III in 1870 and subsequently joined Germany and Austria-Hungary in the League of the Three Emperors in 1873.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Under Alexander's leadership, the Russian Empire engaged in the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878, resulting in the independence of Bulgaria, Montenegro, Romania, and Serbia from the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] His expansionism on the Far Eastern front led to the Amur Annexation, and he also approved Russian military plans on the Caucasian front that culminated in the Circassian genocide.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] While he was disappointed by the results of the Congress of Berlin in 1878, he abided by that agreement.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Among his greatest domestic challenges was a Polish uprising in January 1863, to which he responded by stripping Poland's separate constitution and directly incorporating the kingdom into the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In the period preceding his assassination in 1881, Alexander had been proposing additional parliamentary reforms to counter the rise of nascent revolutionary and anarchistic movements in the region.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Born in Moscow, Alexander Nikolayevich was the eldest son of Nicholas I of Russia and Charlotte of Prussia (eldest daughter of Frederick William III of Prussia and of Louise of Mecklenburg-Strelitz).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] His early life gave little indication of his ultimate potential; until the time of his accession in 1855, aged 37, few imagined that posterity would know him for implementing the most challenging reforms undertaken in Russia since the reign of Peter the Great.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] His uncle Emperor Alexander I died childless.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Grand Duke Konstantin, the next-younger brother of Alexander I, had previously renounced his rights to the throne of Russia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Thus, Alexander's father, who was the third son of Paul I, became the new Emperor; he took the name Nicholas I.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] At that time, Alexander became Tsesarevich as his father's heir to the throne.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In the period of his life as heir apparent (1825 to 1855), the intellectual atmosphere of Saint Petersburg did not favour any kind of change: freedom of thought and all forms of private initiative were suppressed vigorously by the order of his father.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Personal and official censorship was rife; criticism of the authorities was regarded as a serious offence.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The education of the tsesarevich as future emperor took place under the supervision of the liberal romantic poet and gifted translator Vasily Zhukovsky, grasping a smattering of a great many subjects and becoming familiar with the chief modern European languages.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Unusually for the time, the young Alexander was taken on a six-month tour of Russia (1837), visiting 20 provinces in the country.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He also visited many prominent Western European countries in 1838 and 1839.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] As Tsesarevich, Alexander became the first Romanov heir to visit Siberia (1837).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] While touring Russia, he also befriended the then-exiled poet Alexander Herzen and pardoned him.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] It was through Herzen's influence that he later abolished serfdom in Russia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1839, when his parents sent him on a tour of Europe, he met twenty-year-old Queen Victoria and they became acquainted.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Simon Sebag Montefiore speculates that a small romance emerged.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Such a marriage, however, would not work, as Alexander was not a minor prince of Europe and was in line to inherit a throne himself.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1847, Alexander donated money to Ireland during the Great Famine.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He has been described as looking like a German, somewhat of a pacifist, a heavy smoker and card player.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The death of his father gave Alexander a diplomatic headache, for his father was engaged in open warfare in the southwest of his empire.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] On 15 January 1856, the new tsar took Russia out of the Crimean War on the very unfavourable terms of the Treaty of Paris (1856), which included the loss of the Black Sea Fleet, and the provision that the Black Sea was to be a demilitarized zone similar to a contemporaneous region of the Baltic Sea.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] This gave him room to breathe and pursue an ambitious plan of domestic reforms.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Encouraged by public opinion, Alexander began a period of radical reforms, including an attempt not to depend on landed aristocracy controlling the poor, an effort to develop Russia's natural resources, and to reform all branches of the administration.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Boris Chicherin (1828–1904) was a political philosopher who believed that Russia needed a strong, authoritative government by Alexander to make the reforms possible.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II succeeded to the throne upon the death of his father in 1855.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] As Tsesarevich, he had been an enthusiastic supporter of his father's reactionary policies.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] That is, he always obeyed the autocratic ruler.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] But now he was the autocratic ruler himself, and fully intended to rule according to what he thought best.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He rejected any moves to set up a parliamentary system that would curb his powers.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He inherited a large mess that had been wrought by his father's fear of progress during his reign.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Many of the other royal families of Europe had also disliked Nicholas I, which extended to distrust of the Romanov dynasty itself.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Even so, there was no one more prepared to bring the country around than Alexander II.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The first year of his reign was devoted to the prosecution of the Crimean War and, after the fall of Sevastopol, to negotiations for peace led by his trusted counsellor, Prince Alexander Gorchakov.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The country had been exhausted and humiliated by the war.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Bribe-taking, theft and corruption were rampant.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Emancipation Reform of 1861 abolished serfdom on private estates throughout the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] By this edict more than 23 million people received their liberty.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Serfs gained the full rights of free citizens, including rights to marry without having to gain consent, to own property, and to own a business.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The measure was the first and most important of the liberal reforms made by Alexander II.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Polish landed proprietors of the Lithuanian provinces presented a petition hoping that their relations with the serfs might be regulated in a way more satisfactory for the proprietors.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II authorized the formation of committees "for ameliorating the condition of the peasants", and laid down the principles on which the amelioration was to be effected.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The hint was taken: in all provinces where serfdom existed, emancipation committees were formed.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Emancipation was not a simple goal capable of being achieved instantaneously by imperial decree.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] It contained complicated problems, deeply affecting the economic, social, and political future of the nation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander had to choose between the different measures recommended to him and decide, if the serfs would become agricultural laborers dependent economically and administratively on the landlords, or if the serfs would be transformed into a class of independent communal proprietors.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The emperor gave his support to the latter project, and the Russian peasantry became one of the last groups of peasants in Europe to shake off serfdom.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The architects of the emancipation manifesto were Alexander's brother Konstantin, Yakov Rostovtsev, and Nikolay Milyutin.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] On 3 March 1861, six years after his accession, the emancipation law was signed and published.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] A host of new reforms followed in diverse areas.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The tsar appointed Dmitry Milyutin to carry out significant reforms in the Russian armed forces.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Further important changes were made concerning industry and commerce, and the new freedom thus afforded produced a large number of limited liability companies.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Plans were formed for building a great network of railways, partly to develop the natural resources of the country, and partly to increase its power for defense and attack.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Military reforms included universal conscription, introduced for all social classes on 1 January 1874.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Prior to the new regulation, as of 1861, conscription was compulsorily enforced only for the peasantry.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Conscription had been 25 years for serfs who were drafted by their landowners, which was widely considered to be a life sentence.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Other military reforms included extending the reserve forces and the military district system, which split the Russian states into 15 military districts, a system still in use over a hundred years later.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The building of strategic railways and an emphasis on the military education of the officer corps comprised further reforms.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Corporal punishment in the military and branding of soldiers as punishment were banned.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The bulk of important military reforms were enacted as a result of the poor showing in the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] A new judicial administration (1864), based on the French model, introduced security of tenure.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] A new penal code and a greatly simplified system of civil and criminal procedure also came into operation.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Reorganisation of the judiciary occurred to include trial in open court, with judges appointed for life, a jury system, and the creation of justices of the peace to deal with minor offences at local level.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Legal historian Sir Henry Maine credited Alexander II with the first great attempt since the time of Grotius to codify and humanise the usages of war.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Under Alexander's rules Jews could not own land, and were restricted in travel.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] However special taxes on Jews were eliminated and those who graduated from secondary school were permitted to live outside the Pale of Settlement, and became eligible for state employment.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Large numbers of educated Jews moved as soon as possible to Moscow, Saint Petersburg, and other major cities.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Alaska colony was losing money, and would be impossible to defend in wartime against Britain, so in 1867 Russia sold Alaska to the United States for $7.2 million (equivalent to $166 million in 2025).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Russian administrators, soldiers, settlers, and some of the priests returned home.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Others stayed to minister to their native parishioners, who remain members of the Russian Orthodox Church into the 21st century.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander maintained a generally liberal course.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Radicals complained he did not go far enough, and he became a target for numerous assassination plots.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He survived attempts that took place in 1866, 1879, and 1880.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] 1 March] 1881, assassins organized by the Narodnaya Volya (People's Will) party killed him with a bomb.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Emperor had earlier in the day signed the Loris-Melikov constitution, which would have created two legislative commissions made up of indirectly elected representatives, had it not been repealed by his reactionary successor Alexander III.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] An attempted assassination in 1866 started a more conservative period that lasted until his death.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Tsar made a series of new appointments, replacing liberal ministers with conservatives.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Under Minister of Education Dmitry Tolstoy, liberal university courses and subjects that encouraged critical thinking were replaced by a more traditional curriculum, and from 1871 onwards only students from gymnasiums could progress to university.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1879, governors-general were established with powers to prosecute in military courts and exile political offenders.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The government also held show trials with the intention of deterring others from revolutionary activity, but after cases such as the Trial of the 193 where sympathetic juries acquitted many of the defendants, this was abandoned.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] After Alexander II became Emperor of Russia and King of Poland in 1855, he substantially relaxed the strict and repressive regime that had been imposed on Congress Poland after the November Uprising of 1830–1831.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The territories of the former Poland-Lithuania were excluded from liberal policies introduced by Alexander.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The result was the January Uprising of 1863–1864 that was suppressed after eighteen months of fighting.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Hundreds of Poles were executed, and thousands were deported to Siberia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The price of suppression was Russian support for the unification of Germany.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The martial law in Lithuania, introduced in 1863, lasted for the next 40 years.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Native languages, Ukrainian, and Belarusian, were completely banned from printed texts, the Ems Ukase being an example.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The authorities banned use of the Latin script for writing Lithuanian.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Polish language was banned in both oral and written form from all provinces except Congress Poland, where it was allowed in private conversations only.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Nikolay Milyutin was installed as governor and he decided that the best response to the January Uprising was to make reforms regarding the peasants.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He devised a program which involved the emancipation of the peasantry at the expense of the nationalist *szlachta* landowners and the expulsion of Roman Catholic priests from schools.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Emancipation of the Polish peasantry from their serf-like status took place in 1864, on more generous terms than the emancipation of Russian peasants in 1861.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1863, Alexander II re-convened the Diet of Finland and initiated several reforms increasing Finland's autonomy within the Russian Empire, including establishment of its own currency, the Finnish markka.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Liberation of business led to increased foreign investment and industrial development.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Finland also got its first railways, separately established under Finnish administration.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Finally, the elevation of Finnish from a language of the common people to a national language equal to Swedish opened opportunities for a larger proportion of Finnish society.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II is still regarded as "The Good Tsar" in Finland.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] These reforms could be seen as results of a genuine belief that reforms were easier to test in an underpopulated, homogeneous country than in the whole of Russia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] They may also be seen as a reward for the loyalty of its relatively western-oriented population during the Crimean War and during the Polish uprising.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Encouraging Finnish nationalism and language can also be seen as an attempt to dilute ties with Sweden.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] During the Crimean War Austria maintained a policy of hostile neutrality towards Russia, and, while not going to war, was supportive of the Anglo-French coalition.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] During the American Civil War (1861–1865), Russia supported the Union, largely due to the view that the U.S. served as a counterbalance to their geopolitical rival, Great Britain.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1863, the Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Treaty of Paris of 1856 stood until 1871, when Prussia defeated France in the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] During his reign, Napoleon III, eager for the support of the United Kingdom, had opposed Russia over the Eastern Question.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] France abandoned its opposition to Russia after the establishment of the French Third Republic.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Encouraged by the new attitude of French diplomacy and supported by the German Chancellor Otto von Bismarck, Russia renounced the Black Sea clauses of the Paris treaty agreed to in 1856.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] As the United Kingdom with Austria could not enforce the clauses, Russia once again established a fleet in the Black Sea.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] France, after the Franco-Prussian War and the loss of Alsace–Lorraine, was fervently hostile to Germany and maintained friendly relations with Russia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In the Russo-Turkish War (1877–1878) the states of Romania, Serbia, and Montenegro gained international recognition of their independence while Bulgaria and Eastern Rumelia achieved their autonomy from direct Ottoman rule.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Russia took over Southern Bessarabia, lost in 1856.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Russo-Circassian War (1763–1864) concluded as a Russian victory during Alexander II's rule.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Just before the conclusion of the war the Russian Army, under the emperor's order, implemented the mass-killings and extermination of Circassian "mountaineers" in the Circassian genocide, which would be often referred to as "cleansing" and "genocide" in several historic dialogues.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1857, Dmitry Milyutin first published the idea of mass expulsions of Circassian natives.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Milyutin argued that the goal was not to simply move them so that their land could be settled by productive farmers, but rather that "eliminating the Circassians was to be an end in itself – to cleanse the land of hostile elements".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] A large portion of indigenous Muslim peoples of the region were ethnically cleansed from their homeland at the end of the Russo-Circassian War by Russia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] A large deportation operation was launched against the remaining population before the end of the war in 1864 and it was mostly completed by 1867.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Only a small percentage accepted surrender and resettlement within the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The remaining Circassian populations who refused to surrender were thus variously dispersed, resettled, or killed *en masse*.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In April 1876, the Bulgarian population in the Balkans rebelled against Ottoman rule.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Ottoman authorities suppressed the April Uprising, causing a general outcry throughout Europe.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Some of the most prominent intellectuals and politicians on the Continent, most notably Victor Hugo and William Gladstone, sought to raise awareness about the atrocities that the Turks imposed on the Bulgarian population.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] To solve this new crisis in the "Eastern question" a Constantinople Conference was convened by the Great Powers in Constantinople at the end of the year.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The participants in the Conference failed to reach a final agreement.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] After the failure of the Constantinople Conference, at the beginning of 1877, Emperor Alexander II started diplomatic preparations with the other Great Powers to secure their neutrality in case of a war between Russia and the Ottomans.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II considered such agreements paramount in avoiding the possibility of causing his country a disaster similar to the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Russian Emperor succeeded in his diplomatic endeavors.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Having secured agreement as to non-involvement by the other Great Powers, on 17 April 1877 Russia declared war upon the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The treaty and the subsequent Congress of Berlin (June–July 1878) secured the emergence of an independent Bulgarian state for the first time since 1396, and Bulgarian parliamentarians elected the tsar's nephew, Prince Alexander of Battenberg, as the Bulgarians' first ruler.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] For his social reforms in Russia and his role in the liberation of Bulgaria, Alexander II became known in Bulgaria as the "Tsar-Liberator of Russians and Bulgarians".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] A monument to Alexander II was erected in 1907 in Sofia in the "National Assembly" square, opposite to the Parliament building.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The monument underwent a complete reconstruction in 2012, funded by the Sofia Municipality and some Russian foundations.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The inscription on the monument reads in Old-Bulgarian style: "To the Tsar-Liberator from grateful Bulgaria".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] There is a museum dedicated to Alexander in the Bulgarian city of Pleven.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In April 1866, there was an attempt on the emperor's life in St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] To commemorate his narrow escape from death (which he himself referred to only as "the event of 4 April 1866"), a number of churches and chapels were built in many Russian cities.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Viktor Hartmann, a Russian architect, even sketched a design of a monumental gate (which was never built) to commemorate the event.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Modest Mussorgsky later wrote his piano suite *Pictures at an Exhibition*, the last movement of which, "The Great Gate of Kiev", is based on Hartmann's sketches.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] During the 1867 World's Fair in Paris, Polish immigrant Antoni Berezowski attacked the carriage containing Alexander, his two sons and Napoleon III.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] His self-modified double-barreled pistol misfired and struck the horse of an escorting cavalryman.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] On the morning of 20 April 1879, Alexander was briskly walking towards the Square of the Guards Staff and faced Alexander Soloviev, a 33-year-old former student.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Having seen a menacing revolver in his hands, the Emperor fled in a zigzag pattern.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Soloviev fired five times but missed; he was sentenced to death and hanged on 28 May.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The student acted on his own, but other revolutionaries were keen to murder Alexander.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In December 1879, the *Narodnaya Volya* (People's Will), a radical revolutionary group which hoped to ignite a social revolution, organised an explosion on the railway from Livadia to Moscow, but they missed the emperor's train.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] On the evening of 5 February 1880, Stephan Khalturin, also from *Narodnaya Volya*, set off a timed charge under the dining room of the Winter Palace, right in the resting room of the guards a story below, killing 11 people and wounding 30 others.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] After the last assassination attempt in February 1880, Count Loris-Melikov was appointed the head of the Supreme Executive Commission and given extraordinary powers to fight the revolutionaries.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Loris-Melikov's proposals called for some form of parliamentary body, and the Emperor seemed to agree; these plans were never realized.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] 1 March] 1881, Alexander was assassinated in Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] As he was known to do every Sunday for many years, the emperor went to the Mikhailovsky Manège for the military roll call.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He travelled both to and from the *Manège* in a closed carriage accompanied by five Cossacks and Frank (Franciszek) Joseph Jackowski, a Polish noble, with a sixth Cossack sitting on the coachman's left.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The emperor's carriage was followed by two sleighs carrying, among others, the chief of police and the chief of the emperor's guards.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The route, as always, was via the Catherine Canal and over the Pevchesky Bridge.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The street was flanked by narrow pavements for the public.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] A young member of the *Narodnaya Volya* ("People's Will") movement, Nikolai Rysakov, was carrying a small white package wrapped in a handkerchief.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The explosion, while killing one of the Cossacks and seriously wounding the driver and people on the sidewalk, had only damaged the bulletproof carriage, a gift from Napoleon III of France.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Rysakov was captured almost immediately.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Police Chief Dvorzhitzky heard Rysakov shout out to someone else in the gathering crowd.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Dvorzhitzky offered to drive the Tsar back to the Palace in his sleigh.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Tsar agreed, but he decided to first see the culprit, and to survey the damage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He expressed solicitude for the victims.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] To the anxious inquires of his entourage, Alexander replied, "Thank God, I'm untouched".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Nevertheless, a second young member of the *Narodnaya Volya*, Ignacy Hryniewiecki, standing by the canal fence, raised both arms and threw something at the emperor's feet.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He was alleged to have shouted, "It is too early to thank God".
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Later, it was learnt there was a third bomber in the crowd.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Ivan Emelyanov stood ready, clutching a briefcase containing a bomb that was to be used if the other two bombers failed.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander was carried by sleigh to the Winter Palace to his study where almost the same day twenty years earlier, he had signed the Emancipation Edict freeing the serfs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander was bleeding to death, with broken legs, bleeding knees, his stomach ripped open, and his face mutilated.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Members of the Romanov family came rushing to the scene.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The dying emperor was given Communion and Last Rites.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] When the attending physician, Sergey Botkin, was asked how long it would be, he replied, "Up to fifteen minutes." At 3:30 that day, the standard of Alexander II (his personal flag) was lowered for the last time.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II's death caused a great setback for the reform movement.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] One of his last acts was the approval of Mikhail Loris-Melikov's constitutional reforms.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Instead, following his succession, Alexander III, under the advice of Konstantin Pobedonostsev, chose to abandon his father's reforms and went on to pursue a policy of reactionism and greater autocratic power.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The assassination triggered major suppression of civil liberties in Russia, and police brutality burst back in full force after experiencing some restraint under the reign of Alexander II, whose death was witnessed firsthand by his son, Alexander III, and his grandson, Nicholas II.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Vowing not to have the same fate befall them, both emperors brought back repressive state security practices and curtailed the liberal judicial reforms implemented by Alexander II.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Further, both of them assiduously used the Okhrana, a secret police service, to arrest protestors, spy on perceived dissidents, and uproot suspected rebel groups, creating further suppression of personal freedom for the Russian people.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] A series of anti-Jewish pogroms and antisemitic legislation, the May Laws, were yet another outcome of Alexander II's assassination.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1881, the Alexander Church, designed by Theodor Decker and named after Alexander II, was completed in Tampere.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Also, with construction starting in 1883, the Church of the Savior on Blood was built on the site of Alexander's assassination and dedicated in his memory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1838–39, the young bachelor, Alexander made the Grand Tour of Europe which was standard for young men of his class at that time.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] One of the purposes of the tour was to select a suitable bride for himself.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] His father Nicholas I of Russia suggested Princess Alexandrine of Baden as a suitable choice, but he was prepared to allow Alexander to choose his own bride, as long as she was not Roman Catholic or a commoner.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander stayed for three days with the maiden Queen Victoria.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The two got along well, but there was no question of marriage between two major monarchs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In Germany, Alexander made an unplanned stop in Darmstadt.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He was reluctant to spend "a possibly dull evening" with their host Louis II, Grand Duke of Hesse and by Rhine, but he agreed to do so because Vasily Zhukovsky insisted that his entourage was exhausted and needed a rest.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] During dinner, he met and was charmed by Princess Marie, the 14-year-old daughter of Louis II.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He was so smitten that he declared that he would rather abandon the succession than not marry her.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He wrote to his father: "I liked her terribly at first sight.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] If you permit it, dear father, I will come back to Darmstadt after England." When he left Darmstadt, she gave him a locket that contained a piece of her hair.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's parents initially did not support his decision to marry Princess Marie of Hesse.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] There were troubling rumors about her paternity.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Although she was the legal daughter of Louis II, there were rumors that Marie was the biological daughter of her mother's lover, Baron August von Senarclens de Grancy.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's parents worried that Marie could have inherited her mother's tendency to consumption.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's mother considered the Hesse family grossly inferior to the Hohenzollerns and Romanovs.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In April 1840, Alexander's engagement to Princess Marie was officially announced.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In August, the 16-year-old Marie left Darmstadt for Russia.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In December, she was received into the Orthodox Church and received the names *Maria Alexandrovna*.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] On 16 April 1841, aged 23, Tsesarevitch Alexander married Marie in St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander particularly placed hope in his eldest son, Tsesarevich Nicholas.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1864, Alexander II found Nicholas a bride, Princess Dagmar of Denmark, second daughter of King Christian IX of Denmark and younger sister to Alexandra, Princess of Wales and King George I of Greece.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1865, Nicholas died of cerebrospinal meningitis.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's second son, Grand Duke Alexander became heir and married his late brother's fiancée.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The couple married in November 1866, with Dagmar converting to Orthodoxy and taking the name Maria Feodorovna.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander grew estranged from his second son, Grand Duke Alexander.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's favorite child was his daughter, Grand Duchess Marie Alexandrovna.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] He reflected that his daughter had "never caused us anything but joy.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The tsar objected to the queen's request to have his daughter come to England in order to meet her, and after the January 1874 wedding in St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Petersburg, the tsar insisted that his daughter be granted precedence over the Princess of Wales, which the queen rebuffed.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Later that year, after attending the engagement ceremonies of his second surviving son, Vladimir, to Marie of Mecklenburg-Schwerin in Berlin, Alexander II, with his third son, Alexei, accompanying him, made a visit to England.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Disraeli observed of the tsar that "his mien and manners are gracious and graceful, but the expression of his countenance, which I could now very closely examine, is sad.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1866, Alexander II took a mistress, Catherine Dolgorukova, with whom he would father three surviving children.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1880, he moved his mistress and their children into the Winter Palace.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's affair alienated all his children except Alexei and Marie Alexandrovna.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Courtiers spread stories that the dying Empress Marie was forced to hear the noise of Catherine's children moving about overhead, but their respective rooms were actually far.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In May 1880, Grand Duchess Marie Alexandrovna visited Russia to see her dying mother.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] She was horrified to learn that Catherine lived in the Palace and she confronted him.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Shocked by the loss of support from his daughter, he quietly retreated to Gatchina Palace for military reviews.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The quarrel, however, evidently, jolted his conscience enough to lead him to return to St.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Petersburg each morning to ask after his wife's health.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Empress Marie Alexandrovna suffered from tuberculosis.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] 6 July] 1880, Alexander II married his mistress Catherine Dolgorukova morganatically in a secret ceremony at Tsarskoye Selo.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The action scandalized both his family and the court.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] It violated Orthodox custom which required a minimum period of 40 days mourning between the death of a spouse and the remarriage of a surviving spouse, eliciting criticism in foreign courts.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander bestowed on Catherine the title of Princess Yurievskaya and legitimized their children.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II appears prominently in the opening two chapters of Jules Verne's *Michael Strogoff* (published in 1876 during Alexander's own lifetime).
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Emperor sets the book's plot in motion and sends its eponymous protagonist on the dangerous and vital mission which would occupy the rest of the book.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Verne presents Alexander II in a highly positive light, as an enlightened yet firm monarch, dealing confidently and decisively with a rebellion.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The films *Katia* (1938) and *Magnificent Sinner* (1959) depict a highly fictionalized account of the Tsar's romance with the woman who became his second wife.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In *The Tiger in the Well*, Philip Pullman refers to the assassination – though he never names Alexander – and to the pogroms that followed.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The anti-Jewish attacks play an important role in the novel's plot.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Andrew Williams's historical thriller, To Kill A Tsar, tells the story of The People's Will revolutionaries and the assassination through the eyes of an Anglo-Russian doctor living in St Petersburg.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] In the alternate history collection *Back in the USSA* (1997) by Eugene Byrne and Kim Newman, the first known point of divergence is that Alexander lived beyond 1881 and was able to complete his reforms.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Oscar Wilde's first play, *Vera; or, The Nihilists*, written in 1879, features Russian revolutionaries who seek to assassinate a fictional tsar.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] It was originally planned to be staged in 1881 in London, but when Alexander II was actually assassinated that year, the play was canceled.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] The play was produced again in New York in 1883, but to poor reviews, and has remained virtually unknown ever since.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II's reasons to sell Alaska to the United States in 1867 are fictionized in the epilogue of the novel *Forty-Ninth* by Boris Pronsky and Craig Britton, in a form of a letter to Catherine Dolgorukova.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Prior to that, the book explores the events immediately after the first assassination attempt on the Tsar in 1866, as well as the relationship with his brother, Grand Duke Konstantin Nikolayevich.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] Mark Twain describes a short visit with Alexander II in Chapter 37 of *The Innocents Abroad*, describing him as "very tall and spare, and a determined-looking man, though a very pleasant-looking one nevertheless.
[src:alexander-archipelago/alexander-ii-of-russia] It is easy to see that he is kind and affectionate.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] The meaning of the Tlingit name for the island is Winter Town.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Since the late 19th century, it has been the base of the **Annette Island Reserve** of the Metlakatla Alaska Native Community, composed mostly of Tsimshian people.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] This is the only Indian reservation in Alaska as Metlakatla voted to opt out of giving up their lands under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act of the 1970s.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] In 2016 they elected Audrey Hudson as their first Tribal Chairwoman.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] The largest settlement on the island is Metlakatla.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] The federally recognized Metlakatla Indian Community was founded by an unordained Anglican missionary William Duncan and Tsimshian followers who moved with him from their community of Metlakatla in British Columbia after he developed new doctrine and schismatized from his church.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Since the late 19th century, the entire island has been an Indian reserve, a status enacted by Congress when the Tlingit agreed to let the Tsimshian use this territory.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] The Tsimshian set up their government under the Indian Reorganization Act (1934), writing a constitution for electoral government.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] "The mayor, secretary, and treasurer are elected by the general voting membership of the community.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Each of these is elected for a two-year term.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Since the late 1970s, this has been the only remaining reservation in Alaska, as the Metlakatla opted out of giving up their lands for payment under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] In 2016 its Tribal Chairwoman is Audrey Hudson, the first woman to be elected to this role.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] She also serves as mayor, city manager, and police commissioner of the Metlakatla Indian Community.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] The island's population was 1,447 at the 2000 census.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] The island population is composed mainly of Tsimshian people.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] It is a cultural crossroads for Tlingit and Haida Natives as well.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] A network of unimproved roads and trails on the island were developed during years of logging.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] More than 50 years after the United States made a treaty with the Metlakatla Community that promised a cross-island road in exchange for their allowing construction and operation of an airfield on the island, it made good on its word.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] A joint armed forces task force constructed a 15-mile road across the island, completed from 1997 to 2007, which connected Metlakatla on the ocean side to the side facing Ketchikan, where a ferry landing has been built.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] This has not improved access by ferry to the mainland.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] After the Second World War, the airfield was used as a United States Coast Guard Search and Rescue base.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] It served commercial aircraft as well until the 1970s, when the new Ketchikan Airport was built at Gravina Island in the Inside Passage.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] The lower elevations of Annette Island have a Marine west coast climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with windy and wet weather year-round, cool winters, and mild summers, and straddle the border between USDA Plant Hardiness Zones 7 and 8.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Due to its southerly and maritime location, with an annual mean temperature of 47.7 °F (8.7 °C), the Annette Island Airport is one of the warmest locations statewide.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Precipitation falls on most days during the winter, and the seasonal total snowfall of 33.5 inches (85 cm) occurs mostly from November to March, with some accumulation during April.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Snowfall in May and October is relatively rare; warm spells raise the high to 50 °F (10 °C) for several days each month.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] During summer, there is an average of 17 days with 70 °F (21 °C)+ highs, and rain still falls on around half of the days.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Precipitation averages more than 103 inches (2.62 m) annually, with June and July being the driest months and October and November the wettest.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] Extreme temperatures have ranged from −4 °F (−20 °C) on January 30, 1947, up to 93 °F (34 °C) on June 19, 2004, with the temperature having fallen below 0 °F (−18 °C) only on a handful of occasions.
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] In addition, the Annette Island Airport holds the Alaska state monthly record high temperatures for January (66 °F or 19 °C on January 14, 2017), April (82 °F or 28 °C on April 29, 1976), and November (67 °F or 19 °C on November 1, 1970).
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] In 1980, it was made a census-designated place (CDP).
[src:alexander-archipelago/annette-island] It last returned in 1990 and was dissolved as a CDP effective as of the 2000 census.
